<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SDB Plays Important Role to Take In Funds Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- China's fledgling State Development
Bank, operational for just two years, is standing out as one of
the most important links in attracting foreign funds for the
country's key capital projects.
</P>
<P>
It will sign an agreement with Asian Development and Industrial
Bank Association in Seoul early this month for a 100 million-US
dollar syndicated loan to be used by Qilu petro-chemical complex
in Shandong Province for an ethylene expansion project.
</P>
<P>
The loan is co-organized by ADIBA's two members, the Industrial
Bank of Japan and the Industrial Bank of Korea. The State
Development Bank was one of the initiators of ADIBA, which was
established last year.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhang Yong, director of SDB International
Financial Bureau, SDB is to seek about $300 million from abroad
during the second half of this year for major clients, including
the Lingao nuclear power plant in Guangdong, Ertan hydro-electric
Power plant, and an ethylene project in Daqing, northeast China.
</P>
<P>
"We have not decided whether the funds will be raised through
syndicated loans or by issuing bonds," said Zhang.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that SDB will also raise funds for generating sets
for the Three-gorges Dam project.
</P>
<P>
SDB became involved in raising foreign funds in 1995, a year
after the bank was formed to serve government-backed key
construction projects. Up to the present its international
financing activities have been mainly centered on export
credits. Of the some $2.8 billion negotiated last year, 95 percent
were export credits, including $2.3 billion provided by Britain
and France for the Lingao Nuclear Power plant.
</P>
<P>
However, the policy-oriented bank began to use overseas bond
markets this year, by issuing 30 billion yen worth of bonds
(approximately 288 million US dollars) in Japan in February.
</P>
<P>
Encouraged by the success of the first issue, the bank has set
eyes on the American market.
</P>
<P>
"The Yankee bond market has big capacity with bond trading very
active," explained Zhang Yong.
</P>
<P>
"We would have more choices in maturity terms which are better
suited to the capital needs of China' key projects," he added.
</P>
<P>
Zhang is optimistic about SDB's international finance business
expansion since the bank is set to increase its proportion of hard
currency in its total capital assets, from a present miserly 3
percent to 20 percent in next 10 to 15 years.
</P>
<P>
At present, SDB has business links with 44 banks around the
world. It plans to set up branches in major international
financial centers in the future and research and feasibility
studies about to get underway, according to Zhang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
