<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reliability Enhanced For China's Power Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The reliability of large-sized
power-generating units with capacities of more than 100 megawatts
produced in China has risen to more than 86 percent, up 4.4
percentage points from 1991.
</P>
<P>
Vice-minister of Power Industry Lu Yanchang said in Beijing
today that the enhancement in reliability represents a remarkable
improvement in both safe operation and economic efficiency of the
country's large-sized generating units.
</P>
<P>
The senior official noted that China has introduced a
reliability administration system aiming at solving common quality
problems, which proved to be very effective.
</P>
<P>
Under the system, power construction units and power equipment
manufacturers work jointly on the installment and trial operations
of new generating units, and pool the wisdom of both sides in
trying to find out and solve any defects of power equipments,
which might be hidden factors leading to accidents.
</P>
<P>
The vice-minister cited the latest statistics as showing that
by the end of 1995, the country's total installed generating
capacity had reached 217,000 megawatts, of which, almost 59
percent has been contributed by large-sized generating units with
capacities above 100 megawatts.
</P>
<P>
The senior official added that the favorable change in the
structure of generating units signals the fast growth of China's
power sector.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
