<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank to Finance Bangladesh's Rural Credit Scheme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has planned to provide
a soft loan of 105 million US dollars to finance Bangladesh's
rural credit scheme.
</P>
<P>
According to sources today, the loan is a unique attempt to
channel financial assistance to poor people in the countryside,
especially women.
</P>
<P>
"It will use a highly successful government agency as an
intermediary to 100 small non-governmental organizations providing
micro-credit and some big ones," the World Bank's mission chief in
Dhaka Pierre Landell-Mills confirmed, adding that this is a huge
injection of resources spread over 5 years with an aim to reduce
poverty and promote rural income activities -- mundane things like
poultry, fish-farming, trading activities and sewing.
</P>
<P>
The rural credit scheme is expected to reach 2 to 4 million
individuals and benefit millions more, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that nearly half of 120 million Bangladeshis
live below the government-set poverty line of 11.12 US dollars per
month or a daily calorie intake of 2,122.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
