<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Inspects "Best Practices" for Improving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISTANBUL, June 3 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Boutros
Boutros-Ghali today visited the exhibition of "Best Practices" for
improving living environment here organized within the framework
of the Second U.N. Conference on Human Settlements (HABITAT II).
</P>
<P>
Ghali spent most of his time around the Chinese stand, located
in the middle of the exhibition hall and the biggest one occupying
some 500 square meters.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Construction Minister Hou Jie accompanied the
U.N. Chief and introduced China's arduous efforts in improving its
human settlements.
</P>
<P>
Ghali nodded from time to time in approval and appreciation
while fixing his eyes at the pictures showing the rapid
development in housing construction in urban and rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving the Chinese stand, the U.N. chief signed his
name at a pictorial prepared by the Chinese Ministry of
Construction called "Human Settlements In China," specially
dedicated to the HABITAT II.
</P>
<P>
According to a report from the Construction Ministry, from
1979 to 1995, a total of 12.9 billion square meters of housing
completed in China, enabling 160 million urban and rural families
to move into new residence.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, China began to promote the "National Anju Shelter
Program" under which 150 million square meters of low-cost
housing will be built in five years.
</P>
<P>
However, China, the most populated country in the world, is
still facing big challenge and difficulty in its human
settlement.
</P>
<P>
"China shall continue its drive to improve its urban
environment, control the excessive population growth, and upgrade
living conditions in both rural and urban area," said Hou Jie
during today's opening session of HABITAT II, also called "City
Summit." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
