<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Official: Free Economy Guaranteed for Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 3 (Xinhua) -- China's top official in charge of
Hong Kong and Macao affairs reiterated today that the Chinese
government will permit Hong Kong to maintain its free economy
under the "one country, two systems" concept after the British
colony's reversion to China in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Lu Ping, director of the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office of
China's State Council or cabinet, made the remark at a lecture in
Tokyo to an audience that included business executives and
government employees.
</P>
<P>
"The present social and economic structures as well as
citizens' lifestyle in Hong Kong will not change at all," under
the "one country, two systems" concept, Lu told the audience.
</P>
<P>
The region's public servants will also stay intact after 1997,
he said.
</P>
<P>
He turned down observations that some Hong Kong residents are
fleeing to escape the 1997 handover, saying foreign investment
there has been increasing.
</P>
<P>
With the exception of diplomatic relations and defense, Hong
Kong will have full autonomy after China re-establishes its
sovereignty over the region on July 1, 1997, Lu said.
</P>
<P>
If China successfully resolves the Hong Kong issue, it will
help resolve the issues of Macao, a Portuguese colony to be handed
over to China in 1999, and Taiwan in terms of achieving national
reunification, he added.
</P>
<P>
He also urged increased Japanese investment in Hong Kong and
called on the Japanese government to help with the region's
stability by granting visa-exemption to new Hong Kong
passport-holders visiting Japan for business.
</P>
<P>
"After 1997, every investment and economic law will stay the
same as at present. So, Japanese friends, please be at ease at
this point, there will be no change in the economic field," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Lu, on a seven-day visit to Japan through Saturday at the
invitation of the Japanese Foreign Ministry, will meet Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, he met Foreign Minister Yukihiko Ikeda for talks
on Hong Kong's reversion to China next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
