<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, Azerbaijan, Armenia, Georgia Sign Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
signed a cooperation agreement today with Russia's three
Transcaucasian neighbors in a bid to end conflicts in the region.
</P>
<P>
"Russia wants a solid peace throughout the Caucasus
region. That is the foundation of Russia's Caucasus policy,"
Yeltsin said after signing the pact with the presidents of
Azerbaijan, Armenia and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
The agreement on "International Accord, Peace and Economic and
Cultural Cooperation in the Caucasus" condemned "aggressive
separatism, ethnic exclusivity and religious extremism" and called
for joint efforts to settle conflicts in the region.
</P>
<P>
The mountainous region, a volatile patchwork of nearly 50
ethnic groups, has been racked by bloody ethnic and civil wars
which have claimed heavy casualties since the break-up of the
Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin met with Georgian President Eduard Shevardnadze,
Armenian President Levon Ter-Petrosyan and Azeri President Haydar
Aliyev amid tight security at a hilltop sanatorium in the spa town
of Kislovodsk in southern Russia.
</P>
<P>
Referring to last week's ceasefire accord signed between
federal authorities and separatist rebels in Chechnya, Yeltsin
reassured his counterparts that the agreement "opened the way to a
full settlement of the (Chechen) conflict" and that Russia would
stick unswervingly to the plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
