<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Pakistan Tries to Expand Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Boosting trade and economic
relations with other countries and exploring potential foreign
markets have been the first priority of the Pakistani government
in implementing its export strategy.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, a medium-level country in terms of foreign trade, has
long been relying on exports of traditional agricultural, textile
and light engineering items.
</P>
<P>
A narrow export base and a relative low level of foreign trade
are believed to be the main reasons for holding up the country's
development of economic and trade relations with other countries.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government has been trying hard in recent years
to seek a bigger trade share in the world market by taking a
number of bold policy initiatives.
</P>
<P>
For this end, the government has mapped out a strategy to
address the key problem -- lack of diversification -- both in
terms of markets and products.
</P>
<P>
Due to successful marketing, Pakistan exported non-traditional
products worth one billion US dollars during the first 10 months
of the current fiscal year (July 1995 to April 1996).
</P>
<P>
To give it a further boost, Pakistan's Export Promotion Bureau
(EPB) has also prepared a list of export items, pin-pointing 202
non-conventional items for exports in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
The EPB has organized about 60 trade exhibitions abroad to
introduce Pakistan's export items. It plans to hold 30 such
exhibitions a year and to open export display centers in all major
cities around the world.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Pakistani government has been making great
efforts during the last few years to find potential markets for
the country's products and to explore further avenues for boosting
trade links with other countries.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the drive is particularly marked by a
number of successful overseas visits by government leaders.
</P>
<P>
The recent visit to Sweden by Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto was
part of the government's strategy to enhance trade and economic
ties with the European countries which have been Pakistan's
important trading partners over the years.
</P>
<P>
During her tour of Sweden, Benazir Bhutto signed two trade
accords, under which Pakistan will export electrical fans worth
six million US dollars to the Swedish private sector.
</P>
<P>
This is expected to provide a new fillip to the Pakistani
products in the European market and could be termed as a major
achievement in Pakistan's quest to promote exports of
non-traditional products.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has maintained a sound trade relationship with the
European countries on the whole. The European Union (EU) continues
to rank as Pakistan's most important trading partner for both
imports (about 24 percent) and exports (about 29 percent).
</P>
<P>
Along with improving its trade relations with the EU, the
Pakistani government has also ventured to look towards the "East"
to increase exports in real sense.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto also visited Japan, Indonesia and
Brunei this year, which is expected to provide a new impetus to
Pakistan's economic ties with these countries.
</P>
<P>
A major breakthrough was achieved during Benazir's visit to
Indonesia and Brunei with the signing of agreements worth 1.25
billion US dollars for new exports compared with only 100 million
US dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believe that encouraged by the positive outcome,
Pakistan's economic and trade relations with other countries in
this region have the potential for further expansion in the
future.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
