<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retailers Fed Up With Shop Returns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Retailers in the United States,
who are pursuing a customer-friendly service, now find themselves
abused, because they have suffered a lot from a growing number of
return fraud.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of the USA Today, American retailers lose
1 billion U.S. dollars a year to return cheating practices.
</P>
<P>
Many shops and chain stores have a 30-day refund policy. Some
shops have a more lenient policy of allowing customers to make
returns any time for any reason. Therefore, many people would find
out various kinds of excuse to get their money back, according to
the report.
</P>
<P>
Cleveland furniture store owner Fred Crosby said, "I had
someone want to return a 6-month-old sofa so they could take the
money and buy a new one cheaper somewhere else and pocket the
difference."
</P>
<P>
While bad checks and shoplifting account for the bulk of the
retail industry's 26 billion U.S. dollar yearly losses, return
fraud now costs the industry about 1 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
Electronics retailers say radar detectors and video cameras are
bought for vacation trips, then quickly returned. Apparel stores
see a big retail churn in evening wear for class reunions and
weddings mostly during the Christmas and New Year's party season.
In college towns, personal computer sales surge during finals
month, followed by massive returns at semester's end.
</P>
<P>
Since returned items can't be resold, return fraud pushes
prices up, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Retailers now have tightened their return policy by shortening
the days allowing for a return. For example, customers at Best Buy
now have only five days to return laptop computers at the start of
exams. "Even a really good student has trouble getting all his
term papers done in five days," said Mark Germscheid, the shop's
consumer relations supervisor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-03 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bahraini Information Minister on Coup Plot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Bahraini Information Minister
Mohammed al-Muttawa today said his country would like to keep good
relations with all neighboring countries on the basis of
non-interference of internal affairs, according to reports
reaching here from Manama.
</P>
<P>
During a press conference held in Manama today after an
urgent cabinet session, the Bahraini minister expressed hope that
Iran should establish good neighborly relations with other
countries on the basis of mutual respect of sovereignty and
non-interference of each other's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Bahrain today announced the discovery of a conspiracy by a
pro-Iranian terrorist organization to topple the current
government.
</P>
<P>
The Bahraini information minister said that 29 plotters
supported by Iran attempted to topple Bahrain's ruling family,
which belongs to the Sunni sect of Islam, to establish a Shiite
Moslem government similar to that of Iran.
</P>
<P>
Bahrain was recalling its ambassador from Iran, it was
reported.
</P>
<P>
There was no reaction available from Iran on the Bahraini
allegation.
</P>
<P>
Muttawa did not say when the arrests had taken place but said
that the detainees had given full confessions last month.
</P>
<P>
Bahrain was also sending special envoys to the Gulf Cooperation
Council, GCC, countries, Egypt and Syria to explain the details.
</P>
<P>
The Bahraini minister said the plotters belonged to a movement
calling itself " The Military Wing of Hezbollah - Bahrain" and
that it could still be active.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the movement is to stage an armed revolution to
overthrow the Bahraini government by force and replace it with a
pro-Iranian regime, Muttawa said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the GCC member states, which include Saudi Arabia,
Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates (UAE), Bahrain, Oman and Qatar,
Sunday called on Iran not to engage in "acts of sabotage" at the
end of the foreign ministers' meeting held in the Saudi Arabian
capital of Riyadh.
</P>
<P>
The GCC "demands that Iran does not interfere in the internal
affairs of Bahrain and (other GCC) member states," adding that
Iran must not "revert to acts of sabotage and encourage them, and
must respect the independence and sovereignty of the GCC states."
</P>
</TEXT>
