<HEADLINE> Leaders of Zambian Opposition Party Detained </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Four leading members of Zambia's
opposition United National Independence Party (UNIP) headed by
former President Kenneth Kaunda were detained by police here
today.
</P>
<P>
The detainees, UNIP deputy leader Inyambo Yeta, secretary
chief Patrick Goma, finance chairman Rabson Chongo and press
officer Muhabi Lungu, were suspected by the police in connection
with a series of bomb blasts that had taken place in the country
recently.
</P>
<P>
UNIP administrative secretary Basil Kabwe was quoted by
Zambian News Agency as saying that policemen have come to search
the party headquarters, saying they were looking for subversive
materials and explosives. They did not find anything but arrested
the four party leaders, Kabwe added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Sunday, five men were detained by the Zambian
police suspected in connection with the recent explosions at the
official residence of President Frederick Chiluba and offices of
"Times of Zambia".
</P>
<P>
The police charged the five, including three retired army
officers, with being part of Black Mamba, a shadowy movement
opposing the controversial constitution amendment bill which bars
Kaunda from contesting presidency in the general elections to be
held later this year.
</P>
<P>
Police also detained two members of the Zambia Democratic
Congress (ZDC), another opposition party headed by former
Minister Dean Mungombva, last week for unspecified reasons.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda has denied any link with Black Mamba, saying it is a
government plot to discredit him.
</P>
<P>
UNIP and ZDC have expressed their determination not to
recognize the new constitution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
