<HEADLINE> Netanyahu: Arab, Western Countries Understand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister-elect Benjamin
Netanyahu said today that Arab and Western countries understand
Israel wants to continue the peace process based on Likud policy.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, who Sunday night made his first public speech after
winning the elections, said that there was a general positive
reaction in the Arab and western world to his new policies.
</P>
<P>
Attending the celebration party held by the Likud-Gesher-Tsomet
faction at the Knesset (parliament) to toast his election
victory, Netanyahu pledged to continue seeking peace with Israel's
Arab neighbors, whom he urged to join the peace process to
achieve real peace with security for everyone in the region.
</P>
<P>
He said that he plans to meet Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
and Jordanian King Hussein as soon as possible after he forms the
new government.
</P>
<P>
But, Netanyahu put the highest priority on the need to bring
unity, peace and security to Israeli people.
</P>
<P>
In his hectic election campaign, Netanyahu promised that he
will conduct the peace talks with Arabs in a different way from
the current Labor government to ensure security for Israel: to
slow down the pace of Israeli-Palestinian peace process, expand
Jewish settlements and oppose Israeli withdrawal from Golan
Heights seized from Syria.
</P>
<P>
The Arab world, alarmed by Netanyahu's election victory,
remains skeptical about his real intentions at this stage.
</P>
<P>
President Mubarak held today a three-hour intensive talks with
visiting Syrian President Hafez al-Assad to discuss the
implications of Israeli elections.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said that Netanyahu's speech did not inspire optimism,
adding Egypt and Syria will wait and see what policies Netanyahu
government will actually adopt. Al-Assad said that peace process
is not going in a positive way now, and Syria will keep a full
alert on this development.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu met earlier today with Israeli President Ezer
Weizman to brief him on Likud's coalition talks with other
parties and his policy guidelines.
</P>
<P>
According to Israeli laws, Netanyahu is to form the next
government within 45 days after the official publication of
the election results due on Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
