<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Hails Ukraine Nuclear Disarmament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
today praised neighboring Ukraine for having shipped all its
nuclear warheads to Russia.
</P>
<P>
Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma announced Saturday that it
had shipped to Russia the last of the nuclear weapons it inherited
from the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released today, Yeltsin hailed the close
cooperation between Moscow and Kiev in dismantling and
transferring the nuclear warheads, noting the political, economic
and technological difficulties encountered.
</P>
<P>
"Common sense and commitment to international obligations
always took the upper hand," Yeltsin said, pledging further
cooperation with Ukraine in security affairs.
</P>
<P>
Under an accord signed in January 1994 by presidents of Russia,
Ukraine and the Untied States, Kiev agreed to get rid of its
nuclear weapons by this month in exchange for economic assistance
from Moscow and Washington.
</P>
<P>
When the Soviet Union disintegrated in 1991, Ukraine inherited
about 2,000 nuclear warheads left on its territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
