today, the long-awaited meeting, scheduled to be held in Cape
Town, is the last in a series which the commission has held with
party leaders to explain the aims and work of the 17-member panel
which has been probing three decades of human rights abuses in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Buthelezi is the only major political leader not to have met
the commission since it was set up last December.
</P>
<P>
So far, Tutu and Boraine have held talks with National Party
leader F. W. De Klerk, Deputy President Thabo Mbeki, Pan
Africanist Congress leader Clarence Makwetu, Freedom Front leader
Constand Viljoen and Democratic Party leader Tony Leon.
</P>
<P>
There has been persistent efforts to arrange a meeting between
commission officials and Buthelezi, who branded the commission an
ANC witch-hunt aimed at discrediting the party's political
enemies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
