<HEADLINE> British Minister Reaffirms Britain's Support for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Jeremy Hanley, British minister of
state for foreign affairs, today reaffirmed Britain's support for
Lebanon in his talks with Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik al-Hariri
and Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz.
</P>
<P>
At the end of his 90-minute meeting with al-Hariri, Hanley
said his visit to Lebanon was aimed at stressing "Britain's
standing on Lebanon's side in the peace process" in the Middle
East region.
</P>
<P>
On the situation in the region in light of the Israeli
elections last week, the British minister said that his
government would "urge the new Israeli government to resume the
peace process and to continue what the previous Israeli
government had done" on the Syrian-Israeli and Palestinian-Israeli
tracks.
</P>
<P>
Hanley noted that he delivered a message to the Lebanese prime
minister from British Prime Minister John Major, which "reiterates
the friendship between the two countries."
</P>
<P>
The message also contained the support of Britain, the
Europeans, the United States for the efforts exerted for the
realization of peace in the region, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to urge Israel to implement (U.N. Security
Council) Resolution 425, which provides for an Israeli withdrawal
from the occupied Lebanese lands," he added.
</P>
<P>
After his 70-minute meeting with Boueiz, the British minister
said that he had "good talks" with the Lebanese prime minister
and the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
"We are here to discuss the Israeli elections and the
reactions on them and we encourage the Lebanese to judge the new
Israeli government by its acts and not by its positions launched
during the election campaigns," he said.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question on whether the peace process would be
negatively affected by the victory of Benjamin Netanyahu, the
leader of the rightwing Likud Party, in the Israeli elections,
Hanley said that it would be in Israel's interests to continue
the peace process, and it would be in the new Israeli prime
minister's interests to pursue the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The British minister has left the Lebanese capital this
afternoon for Damascus on the second leg of his tour in the
region. 
</P>
