<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea Holds 11th Trial of Two Former Presidents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The 11th trial session on mutiny and
treason charges involving former presidents Chun Doo-hwan and Roh
Tae-woo was held at the Seoul District Court here today.
</P>
<P>
Also standing trial at the court were Chun's 11 close aides,
including former first army corps commander Hwang Young-si.
</P>
<P>
Chun Doo-hwan admitted today that he and his close aides
formulated a plan to settle the political tensions in the country
in May 1980, but again rejected the prosecution's charges that the
aim of their move was to usurp the power.
</P>
<P>
Defense lawyers today completed their cross-examination of the
13 defendants involved in the military revolt on December 12, 1979
and began to question eight defendants involved in the bloody
crackdown of the civil uprising on May 18, 1980, in Kwangju,
capital of South Korea's South Cholla Province.
</P>
<P>
In earlier cross-examination by defense layers, all defendants
alleged that their arrests of the then Army Chief of Staff Chung
Sung-hwa and several other loyal generals on December 12, 1979,
was not a mutiny, but a legitimate and unavoidable action needed
to investigate the assassination of President Park Chung-hee.
</P>
<P>
A total of 16 former South Korean army officers including Chun
and Roh have been indicted for mutiny or treason, or both. The
mutiny and treason charges respectively stem from their roles in
the 1979 military revolt and the 1980 military crackdown of the
Kwangju civil uprising.
</P>
<P>
Chun Doo-hwan, who loomed large as the army strongman after the
1979 military revolt, seized power on August 27, 1980, and ruled
the country until February 1988. He was followed by Roh Tae-woo
who stepped down in February 1993.
</P>
<P>
The two former presidents, who were arrested last year, have
also been indicted for graft charges because they accepted huge
bribes from businessmen while in office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
