<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Foreign Ministers Approve European-only Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, June 3 (Xinhua) -- After more than two years'
wrangling, the foreign ministers of NATO's 16 member states today
ratified a plan to set up European-only military units which will
exclude U.S. troops.
</P>
<P>
The decision gives the green light to the creation of Combined
Joint Task Forces (CJTFs) which will be used by European nations
for peacekeeping or relief missions.
</P>
<P>
The CJTFs will not have U.S. participation but will use
American military hardware, such as intelligence, communications
and airlift assets.
</P>
<P>
The plan, adopted at the spring session of the North Atlantic
Council, gives European nations more flexibility and resources to
deal with regional crises in Europe.
</P>
<P>
For example, members of the 10-nation Western European Union
(WEU), Europe's defense organization which complements NATO, could
conduct an operation using American equipment without involving US
ground troops.
</P>
<P>
However, the North Atlantic Council, made up of representatives
of the 16 NATO members, will authorize missions for the new
forces, which will, in effect, give the United States the power of
veto.
</P>
<P>
Although the Europeans could, under the new plan, mount their
own peacekeeping operations, a U.S. senior official told reporters
that he expected such operations to be "smaller scale missions"
and "very few and far between."
</P>
<P>
The principle of the CJTFs was first proposed by the United
States at a NATO summit in January 1994 with the aim of shifting
more of the alliance's security responsibilities to Europe.
</P>
<P>
But the plan stalled due to differences between Washington and
Paris over the U.S. role and influence over the use of NATO staff,
equipment and headquarters.
</P>
<P>
France was initially opposed to parts of the plan because of
its 30-year refusal to place its forces under NATO command.
</P>
<P>
The breakthrough has been made possible by the recent
willingness of the French to take part in NATO activities and
institutions, including participation in the Peace Implementation
Force in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The ratification of the CJTFs concept also gives non-NATO
nations, especially countries in central and eastern Europe, the
chance to participate in the more flexible and mobile forces.
</P>
<P>
Over the next six months, NATO military leaders will put the
concept into operation, including identifying where the CJTFs
should be headquartered and who should command them.
</P>
<P>
At the one-day meeting, the foreign ministers also approved the
creation of a political-military policy coordination group, made
up of two members per delegation, to smooth decision-making within
the alliance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
