<HEADLINE> Stocks Fall Sharply, Dollar Declines in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Stocks fell sharply in Tokyo today
amid news reports of a virtual bankruptcy of a nonbank
institution, and the U.S. dollar eased against the yen, slipping
to the mid-107 yen level.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues closed at
21,588.52, down 367.67 points, or 1.67 percent, from Friday's
close.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo Stock Price Index, covering all first-section stocks
on the Tokyo Stock Exchange, dropped 21.93 points, or 1.30
percent, to 1,658.64.
</P>
<P>
The dollar's decline against the yen on today's Tokyo Foreign
Exchange was due in part to the U.S. currency's weakness against
the German mark and partly to a late afternoon rumor in the market
of a possible default by the Brazilian government.
</P>
<P>
The dollar was quoted at 107.62-65 yen at 5 p.m., down from
108.15-18 yen at 9 a.m.. It moved between 107.50 and 108.29 yen
during the day's session. 
</P>
