<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO FMs Meeting Ends With Call for Shaping New NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The spring session of the North
Atlantic Council ministerial meeting ended today in the historic
symbol of a divided Europe with a final communique which calls for
efforts to shape a new NATO to meet post-Cold War challenges.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting of foreign ministers from the 16 NATO member
countries was dominated by the issue of the alliance's adaptation
and reform process.
</P>
<P>
Other main topics were the NATO-led peace Implementation Force
(IFOR) operation in Bosnia, NATO's enlargement, the Partnership for
Peace program and NATO's relations with Russia and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers stated in the final communique that it is
now the moment to take a "decisive step" forward in making NATO
"increasingly flexible and effective" to meet new challenges.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to carry further the ongoing adaptation of the
alliance's structures of which an essential part is to build a
European Security and Defense Identity (ESDI) within NATO.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also agreed to enhance their contribution to
security and stability throughout the Euro-Atlantic area by
broadening and deepening their dialogue and cooperation with
partners through the partnership program.
</P>
<P>
They reaffirmed NATO's intention to further develop their
important relations with Russia and Ukraine while maintaining
openness to new members through the established enlargement
process.
</P>
<P>
In the final communique, three fundamental objectives were
listed which will guide NATO's actions to improve the alliance's
capability, namely ensuring the alliance's military effectiveness,
preserving the transatlantic link and developing the ESDI within
the alliance.
</P>
<P>
At today's meeting, the 16 foreign ministers ratified the plan
to establish the Combined Joint Task Forces.
</P>
<P>
Under this new plan, European allies will be allowed to run,
under the banner of the West European Union (WEU), military
operations (peacekeeping or relief missions) in a regional crisis
without U.S. participation but use NATO's command structures,
intelligence, logistics and communications resources.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also approved the establishment of the Policy
Coordination Group for closer coordination of political and
military viewpoints to smooth the way for decision-making.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of the IFOR mission in Bosnia, the ministers
stated that the IFOR will be maintained at approximately its
current force levels until after the elections which will have to
take place in September at the latest under the peace agreement,
and will retain its overall capability until December, when the
IFOR's mandate comes to an end.
</P>
<P>
They stressed that NATO will develop a "strong, stable and
enduring partnership" with Russia. The partnership between the two
sides is an essential element of security in the Euro-Atlantic
area, they said.
</P>
<P>
Other issues such as NATO's relations with the WEU and the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, the
Conventional Armed Forces in Europe follow-up conference in Vienna
and the dialogue with the Mediterranean countries were also
discussed at the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
