<HEADLINE> Iran Denies Involvement in Bahrain's Internal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Iran today strongly refuted
allegations of any Iranian interference in the international
affairs of other countries, including Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
Mahmoud Mohammadi, spokesman of the Foreign Ministry, denied
Bahrain's allegations that Iran was involved in a plot for
toppling the ruling Al Khalifa family of Bahrain, saying they were
"totally baseless."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman was quoted by Iran's official news agency IRNA as
saying that the Islamic Republic of Iran "advises the Bahraini
government against being influenced by the conspiracies of the
enemies of the Islamic Ummah."
</P>
<P>
He said the Bahrain stance was a result of instigation by
outsiders, and will have no outcome other than straining
bilateral ties and paving the way for presence of foreign powers
in the region. But he did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi reiterated that Tehran had always been for regional
cooperation in order to restore stability and security.
</P>
<P>
Bahrain today announced a defeat of coup d'etat plotted by Iran
and the arrest of 29 plotters.
</P>
<P>
Bahraini Information Minister Mohammed al-Muttawa said that the
29 plotters supported by Iran attempted to topple Bahrain's ruling
family, who belongs to the Sunni sect of Islam, to establish a
Shiite Moslem government similar to that of Iran.
</P>
<P>
He said Bahrain was recalling its ambassador from Iran, but
would not server ties.
</P>
<P>
Muttawa did not say when the arrests were made but said that
the detainees had given full confessions last month.
</P>
<P>
The Bahraini minister said the plotters belonged to a movement
calling itself " The Military Wing of Hezbollah - Bahrain" and
that it could still be active.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the movement is to stage an armed revolution to
overthrow the Bahraini government by force and replace it with a
pro-Iranian regime, Muttawa said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
