<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Promote Standard of Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government is
planning to extend Teachers' Resource Centers (TRCS) to the
national level in the coming five years as a means to promote the
standard of education in the country.
</P>
<P>
Principal Secretary in the Ministry of Education and Culture,
S. Odunga made the remarks today while opening a seven-day
workshop on the role of TRCS held in Arumeru District, Arusha
region, northern Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
He said the TRCS now involved only 5,000 teachers in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Africa faces a severe education crisis as students'
achievement is reaching low levels while the 21st century puts
science and technology as of prime importance for development,
Odunga said. He attributed poor education foundation in the
region to, among others, the lack of teaching materials including
textbooks.
</P>
<P>
He said that TRCS is considered by the government of Tanzania
as a mechanism for solving educational problems facing teachers
in a meaningful and effective manner since it deals with teachers
who are major actors in the system of education.
</P>
<P>
The TRCS address the most critical problems in schools and
will be effective in decentralization of education system away
from the central government, but based on local resources.
</P>
<P>
The seven-day workshop financed by the Danish Agency for
International Development (DANIDA) through the Danish Volunteers
Services (CVS) has drawn participants from Zimbabwe, Mozambique,
Uganda, Lesotho, Zambia, Kenya, Malawi, Tanzania, South Africa
and Eritrea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
