<HEADLINE> Mubarak, Assad Call for United Arab Front </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and
his Syrian counterpart Hafez al-Assad today called for a united
Arab front in dealing with the new Israeli government led by Prime
Minister-elect Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference following their three-hour talks,
the two leaders urged Arabs to take time to see what policies
Netanyahu would follow.
</P>
<P>
The summit between Mubarak and al-Assad came amid concerns of
the Arab world that right-wing Likud leader Netanyahu's victory in
last week's Israeli elections would slow down the Middle East
peace process.
</P>
<P>
"Things are not going in a positive way," al-Assad told the
press conference. "We have to be fully alert and on guard."
</P>
<P>
He said that the resumption of Syrian-Israeli talks is "out of
the question now."
</P>
<P>
Al-Assad, who was met by Mubarak at the airport when he arrived
in Cairo earlier today, said he believes the United States is
serious in its efforts to bring about peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said during his election campaigns that he would take
a tougher line in peace negotiations with the Palestinians and
Syria than Shimon Peres, the outgoing prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said he rejected the return of Golan Heights to Syria
and holding talks with the Palestinians on the future of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Israel occupied the Golan and Arab east Jerusalem in the 1967
Middle East war. Syria demands the return of the strategic plateau
as a prerequisite for making peace with Israel, while the
Palestinians want to establish an independent state with Jerusalem
as its capital.
</P>
<P>
Israel has regarded Jerusalem as its united, eternal capital.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said at the press conference that if the Israelis,
under the leadership of Netanyahu, want a real and comprehensive
peace, the Arabs are ready for peace.
</P>
<P>
His talks with al-Assad dealt with Egyptian-Syrian relations
and the current situation in the region in the wake of the Israeli
elections, Mubarak said.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian president's visit to Egypt came just one day after
his meeting with Lebanese President Elias Hrawi in Latakia, Syria.
</P>
<P>
Al-Assad and Hrawi held talks Sunday to coordinate their
stances on the peace process following Netanyahu's upset win over
Peres in the elections, the Cairo press reported today.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Mubarak, King Hussein of Jordan and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat are expected to hold a tripartite summit in
Aqaba, Jordan, for similar purpose. 
</P>
</TEXT>
