<HEADLINE> 1.8 Million S.Africans Infected With Hiv in 1995 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 3 (Xinhua) -- More than 1.8 million people
or 4.3 percent of South Africa's total population were infected
with HIV in 1995, Health Minister Nkosazana Zuma said today.
</P>
<P>
In her budget speech in the senate in Cape Town, Zuma said the
Department of Health had found in annual surveys that the highest
hiv infection rates were among women in their early twenties.
</P>
<P>
''From 1994 to 1995 we saw an increase in the overall
prevalence of HIV infection from 7.6 percent to 10.4 percent
among women attending antenatal clinics,'' said the minister.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that more than 13 percent of South African
women between the ages of 20 to 24 were infected with hiv, while
11.03 percent of women between 25 and 29 were infected.
</P>
<P>
Zuma said of particular concern was that the hiv infection
rate among pregnant teenagers was as high as 9.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
She stressed that teenagers constituted a high risk group for
hiv infection and hence the intervention programs needed to
continue focusing on this group to prevent them from hiv
infections and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
These statistics were a real concern as they had serious
implications for the entire social and economic development of
the country, she said, adding that ''HIV/AIDS is a real threat to
the lives of our general population in particular young adults''.
</P>
<P>
While criticising the previous government had done little to
address the issue, Zuma said the present government had allocated
80 million Rand (about 18.6 million U.S.Dollars) in its 1996/97
budget to fight aids. 
</P>
</TEXT>
