<HEADLINE> Turkey's Coalition Government Possibly to be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's parliament today voted
overwhelmingly to open a debate on a censure motion submitted by
the Islamic Welfare Party (RP) against the center-right coalition
government led by Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz.
</P>
<P>
The voting results of 317 to 124 suggest that the parliament
would oust the government possibly on Saturday. To unseat the
government, 276 votes are needed.
</P>
<P>
Most of the deputies from the True Path Party (DYP), the
coalition partner, joined the deputies from the RP, the Republican
People's Party (CHP) and the Grand Unity Party (BBP) in voting for
the opening of the debate against the government.
</P>
<P>
The debate will be held on June 6 and the vote will be set for
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Deputies from the Democratic Left Party (DSP) stayed away from
the voting today and once again gave their indirect support to
Yilmaz. Besides 75 DSP deputies, 33 others, some possibly from
the DYP, stayed away from the vote.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that there are some DYP mavericks who oppose DYP
Chairwoman Tansu Ciller.
</P>
<P>
The RP became the first party in December's general elections,
but was shut out of power by the coalition set up by Yilmaz and
Ciller.
</P>
<P>
Since the coalition government was set up in March, Yilmaz and
Ciller have not been in good cooperation and have been fighting
against each other. 
</P>
</TEXT>
