<HEADLINE> UNEP Boss Calls for Envoirnmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Executive Director of the
United Nations Environment Program (UNEP), Elizabeth Dowdeswell,
issued a statement here today marking the World Environment Day
which falls on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Dowdeswell said at the heart of the World Environment Day
celebrations, which will be held in Istanbul, is the belief that
every individual human being has the right to enjoy clean air,
pure water and the benefits of our biological diversity.
</P>
<P>
She said most people want to improve the quality of their
lives, having a clean, decent, safe home in which to live and
raise a family.
</P>
<P>
However, the UNEP boss said, the quality of life is threatened
by the explosive and continuing growth rates of urban areas.
</P>
<P>
And now, cities are expanding into fragile ecosystems, adding
that nearly 40 percent of cities with a population of more than
500,000 are located on coasts.
</P>
<P>
She also said air pollution already exceeds health standards
in many mega cities, urging that cities future development to be
based on environmental considerations.
</P>
<P>
"One thing is clear, and it is that the fate of cities will
determine more and more not only the fate of nations, but also of
our planet," She noted.
</P>
<P>
If cities are to continue to be the engines for economic
growth, their future development has to be based on
considerations that are environmentally sustainable,she added.
</P>
<P>
Ms Dowdeswell said: " The ultimate solution to every
environmental problem, from deforestation to pollution, lies in
each of us taking the responsibility for our own acts and not
giving up hope." 
</P>
</TEXT>
