<HEADLINE> Percentage of New York High School Graduates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The percentage of New York City
public high school students graduating in the traditional four
years has reached a five-year low, according to the city's Board
of Education.
</P>
<P>
Examing what happened to all the students in the city's schools
who would have been expected to graduate in the classes of 1991
through 1995, a report, which was released on Sunday by the Board,
shows that in the Spring 1995, 48 percent of the students who had
started high school four years before had graduated, three percent
lower than the graduation rate for the class of 1991, and 33.7 of
the students still were in school after four years, 5.2 percent up
from the class of 1991.
</P>
<P>
For the class of 1992, 30 percent of students who had started
high school four years before went on to to a fifth year of
school. An additional 13 percent continued into a sixth year, and
7.6 percent stayed for a seventh year.
</P>
<P>
As result, there are now more 19-,20-and 21-year-old students
than ever in classrooms, and this year, about 10 percent of the
city's 300,000 high school students are over 18, education
officials said.
</P>
<P>
The report did not explain why this abnormal situation occurred
in the city's high schools, only saying that these students have
confronted a variety of obstacles to finishing high school on
schedule, such as social and family problems.
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing on Sunday, John C. Fager of the Parents
Coalition for Education, a citywide advocacy group, called on
City's departments concerned to give more attention to the
declining four-year graduation rate. He said," It's a bad news for
the kids who have to spend five and six and seven years finishing
high school and it's a bad news for the taxpayers because this
means a lot of extra expenditures.
</P>
<P>
School officials said that about 6,000 u.s. dollars are needed
to educate each child. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
