<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Street Vendors Disappear in Lagos' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- There is a saying that Nigeria's
Commercial Center of Lagos has been prosperous because it has so
many street vendors.
</P>
<P>
They joked that in the six million population of the city, one
million are street traders.
</P>
<P>
And about half of the selling and buying of local people's
daily necessities are made on the street.
</P>
<P>
''Lagos is famous in Africa for its banking, population and
street trading,'' Lagosians say.
</P>
<P>
But the bankruptcy of over half of the 300 banks in Lagos has
forced the government to announce a series of new rules and
regulations. The overcrowded population of the city has forced
the government to build another capital called Abuja in the
center of the country.
</P>
<P>
Today, in the middle of the International Environment Year,
the Nigerian government acted on the street vendors.
</P>
<P>
''The street trading is jeopardizing the nations's
environment, causing traffic jams and damaging the country's
foreign investment environment,'' said an decree released by the
Lagos state government today.
</P>
<P>
No wonder a drive around the city on the ''busy Monday'' did
not show up the much familiar scene: the street vendors who keep
on knocking at your car screens and doors as you are blocked by
traffic jams.
</P>
<P>
And there is no sign of them running to and for across the
streets to bargain a good price for their small goods at the risk
of their own lives and causing danger for motorists.
</P>
<P>
The hard measures announced by the government worked. At least
for the time being.
</P>
<P>
The new decree imposes a fine ranging from 5,000 Naira to
15,000 Naira (around 65 to 200 US Dollars) or a term of
imprisonment ranging from six months to one year, both on the
street vendors and on the buyers.
</P>
<P>
''Don't be surprised if you see a car owner being arrested and
prosecuted for just doing his shopping right in the middle of the
street or a housewife who prefers to buy her wares by the
roadside instead of going into the market,'' said a government
official.
</P>
<P>
It also prohibits selling on pedestrian bridges and the
extension of shops to walkways.
</P>
<P>
On why the state intends to prosecute the buyers, he said:
''If there are no buyers, there won't be sellers.''
</P>
<P>
He added that a special tribunal has been set up by the Lagos
State Judicial Court on street trading.
</P>
<P>
But vendors say the measure are ''simply killing us''.
</P>
<P>
In the country where the monthly income for an ordinary family
is as low as no more than 1,000 Naira (around 12 US Dollars), no
street vendors can afford to pay the fine of 5,000 to 15,000
Naira.
</P>
<P>
''They (the fine) are worse than imprisonment'' said a street
vendor, who sneaked at the corner of a street in the Victoria
Island, Lagos.
</P>
<P>
''But apart from selling things in the street, what else can
we do? What do they (the government) want from us?'' he
complained.
</P>
<P>
''Go to the market and do your business illegally,'' that's
the answer from the government officials.
</P>
<P>
They say the street vendors produce garbage, noise and crowd
the street, they say over one third of the traffic accidents in
the city are caused by the street traders.
</P>
<P>
Street trading is a way of avoiding paying government taxes.
It is also a way of escaping marketing rent.
</P>
<P>
''It is small business and it causes a big problem to our
environment and city administration,'' an environment expert
shrugged.
</P>
<P>
''It's a good thing they finally disappeared,'' said a driver.
</P>
<P>
Will they reappear? 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
