<HEADLINE> Rotary International District Conference Opens in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The 71st Rotary International
District 9200 Conference was officially opened here today by
Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni.
</P>
<P>
The three-day conference, with "Act with Integrity, Serve with
Love, Work for Peace" as its theme, will mainly review the
district's projects and explore ways to further Rotary
International's goals of world understanding, peace, education,
health and communication.
</P>
<P>
In his opening address, Museveni said the Ugandan government
highly appreciates the underlying character of Rotary
International. He said that Uganda believes that the discipline
and self sacrifice on which Rotary International is built, are
the kind of building blocks Uganda needs to build itself.
</P>
<P>
He commended the contribution of non-government organizations
(NGOs), including Rotary International, to social services in
Uganda.
</P>
<P>
He clarified that NGO will continue to be very important
partners in the delivers of services to the people as government
alone will not meet the demand for social services for a long
time to come.
</P>
<P>
He urged Rotarians in District 9200 to individually and
collectively work for peace. He said that without peace their
district has no future.
</P>
<P>
Tonny Serrano of South Africa, representing President of
Rotary International Herbert Brown, thanked President Museveni
for his encouragement to the Rotarians.
</P>
<P>
He said that 56 million US Dollars have been contributed
by Rotarians throughout the world to eradicate polio in Africa,
which he called the last bastion of the disease in the world.
</P>
<P>
This is the third annual Rotary International district
conference held in Uganda since the Rotary movement started in
the country in the early 1950s.
</P>
<P>
Present at the conference are over 1,000 Rotarians from Rotary
International District 9200 which includes Eritrea, Ethiopia,
Kenya, Mauritius, Tanzania, Reunion, Seychellyes, Somalia,
Djibouti and Uganda, and others from South Africa, the United
Kingdom and the United States. 
</P>
