<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: A Third of Poor Kids in Working Families </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- More than one-third of all the
poor children in the United States, or about 5.6 million, are
members of "working poor" families, said a survey released on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Only 14 percent of children in working poor families were born
to a teen-age mother. Most were born to women over 25 years old
and half lived in married, two-parent households where at least
one parent -- usually the father -- worked all year, said the
report by the Annie E. Casey Foundation, which cited federal
statistics.
</P>
<P>
The findings indicate that between 1989 and 1994, when the
overall economy was strong, conditions became worse for the
working poor. The number of children in such families increased by
30 percent.
</P>
<P>
The problem is caused by a decline in the value of low-skill
labor, said Douglas Nelson, executive director of the Casey
Foundation, a Baltimore-based charitable organization that focuses
on disadvantaged children.
</P>
<P>
In the late 1960s, a young adult working full time at the
minimum wage could keep a family of three out of poverty, he said.
"In 1994, a household head working full time at the minimum wage
earned only 70 percent of the income needed to lift a family of
three out of poverty."
</P>
<P>
According to researchers, an annual income of 11,821 dollars
for a family of three was considered the poverty level for the
survey.
</P>
<P>
The survey found that from 1985 to 1993, the years statistics
are available, the number of babies born weighing less than 5.5
pounds had increased 6 percent nationwide.
</P>
<P>
The birth rate to mothers aged 15-17 jumped 23 percent and the
number of violent teen deaths rose 10 percent over the same
period. However, the total number of infant deaths over that time
span dropped 21 percent, the survey said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Factory Orders Drop Third Time in Four Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 4 (Xinhua) -- With a decline of 0.1 percent in
April, the factory orders in the U.S. dropped for the third time
in the first four months of this year.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Commerce Department reported here today that orders
for both durable and nondurable goods totaled a seasonally
adjusted 309.1 billion dollars in April, down from 309.5 billion
in March when a 1.7 percent jump was posted, the only increase
this year.
</P>
<P>
Orders for durable goods plunged by 1.9 percent in April but
those for nondurable goods rose 2 percent, the sixth advance in
seven months.
</P>
<P>
The report said that falling aircraft bookings had offset an
increase of motor vehicle sales. Transportation orders fell 12.8
percent, nearly erasing a 14.6 percent jump in the previous month.
It was the largest drop since a 14.8 percent decline in July 1994.
</P>
<P>
Excluding the volatile transportation sector, orders rose 1.9
percent, the fourth increase in the last five months.
</P>
<P>
Orders are considered a key gauge of the nation's manufacturing
strength and a decline could mean slower production and job
growth.
</P>
<P>
The backlog of unfilled orders fell 0.2 percent, the first
decline since August. A shrinking backlog suggests businesses are
able to meet consumer demand with current production facilities
and manpower.
</P>
<P>
But inventories, another sign of future activity, edged up 0.2
percent, wiping out an identical decline a month earlier.
</P>
<P>
Shipments, a measure of current activity, rose 1.7 percent, the
third straight increase. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
