<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Police to Enhance Cooperation With Mainland Counterpart </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Police will strengthen
cooperation with its counterpart in the mainland in combating
cross-border crimes.
</P>
<P>
Eddie Hui Ki-on, commissioner of Hong Kong Police, said here
today that joint efforts will be made in tackling problems of
illicit fish bombs, illegal pregnant immigrants, and pick
pocketing in Lo Wu -- a traveler pass between Hong Kong and the
mainland.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner made the remarks after a ten-day visit to the
mainland, where he met with public security officers in
Guangdong, Beijing and Shanghai. The trip, which enhanced mutual
understanding and cooperation, proved to be a success, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the commissioner, Hong Kong Police has sought
assistance from Guangdong Provisional Public Security Bureau to
trace the origin of fish bombs discovered in the territory.
</P>
<P>
A total of 319 kg of fish bombs were seized in the first
quarter of this year, outweighing those captured in the same
period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Commissioner Hui also held a thorough discussion with Guangdong
 officers on clamping down on pick pocketing in Lo Wu. The number
of reported cases in 1995 dropped compared to 1994.
</P>
<P>
Intelligence exchange will be strengthened between the two
places to deal with the problem of influx of illegal immigrants
into Hong Kong, particularly pregnant ones, said Hui.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
