<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Australia Retreats on Greenhouse Commitment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Australian government made a
U-turn today in the course of supporting the international drive
to cut greenhouse gas emissions.
</P>
<P>
The coalition government issued a declaration that Australia
would seek exemption from the international agreement on
greenhouse emissions to be reached under the Framework Convention
on Climate Change next year.
</P>
<P>
The joint declaration of the foreign, environment and resources
ministers said the government would not undertake the binding
target and timetable for emission reduction.
</P>
<P>
Four years ago, Australia was among the world's first group of
countries signing the Framework Convention, which foreshadowed
that developed countries should stabilize greenhouse emissions at
the 1990 level by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
"Australia will insist that the outcome of current
international negotiations on climate change safeguards
Australia's particular economic and trade interests," said today's
declaration.
</P>
<P>
"Australia is particularly vulnerable to the economic impacts
of coordinated OECD-wide measures to reduce greenhouse gas
emissions," it said.
</P>
<P>
Local media said the declaration was the first major victory of
industries over the coalition government, but experts said it was
a big setback for the global efforts to combat climate change.
</P>
<P>
Australia has the world's highest per capita level of
greenhouse gas emission and ranks the sixth in total output of
greenhouse gases.
</P>
<P>
Though the former Labor government had undertaken to limit the
growth of greenhouse emissions at 3 percent above the 1990 level
by 2000, the coalition government's new decision means that local
industries can even break that mark now.
</P>
<P>
Local industries have lobbied strongly for the government to
adopt a softer stance on greenhouse gas emissions, as 81 percent
of the energy used in Australia is from coal fire.
</P>
<P>
Major consumers of coal energy, such as the coal industry and
the aluminum industry, expected their total output of greenhouse
gases to rise, not to fall, by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Under the current voluntary agreement between industries and
the government, there are no penalties if industries fail to meet
the emission target.
</P>
<P>
The coalition government has also effectively ruled out the
introduction of carbon taxes that discourage inefficient use of
fuel.
</P>
<P>
"We are the world's largest coal exporter and we specialize in
greenhouse-gas intensive exports such as petroleum products, basic
metals, chemicals, cereals and livestock," the declaration said.
</P>
<P>
The coalition government promised to fund environmental
projects with the proceeds of selling the government-owned Telstra
company. But the sale of the telecommunication company has yet to
be approved by the Senate that was overwhelmingly opposed to the
proposal.
</P>
<P>
Greenpeace Australia's climate change campaigner Keith Tarlo
said it was "grossly unfair" to expect the developing countries to
stand at the same starting point in reducing greenhouse gas
emissions as the developed countries.
</P>
<P>
Australian Democrats environment spokesman Meg Lees said the
coalition government would risk a repeat of last year's
embarrassing situation in Berlin when it goes to Geneva this July.
</P>
<P>
Australia faced isolation at the first Conference of Parties
under the Framework Convention in Berlin in March-April, 1995,
when it insisted that developing countries should share the burden
with developed countries to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
</P>
<P>
With the United States and Japan indicating their support for
more enforceable measures at the second meeting of the parties
scheduled for Geneva in July, Australia has to be prepared to
"sing solo," a local newspaper said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
