<HEADLINE> Farmers In Shaanxi Give 150 Relics to Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Three farmers in Fufeng County,
northwest China's Shaanxi Province, have handed over 150 cultural
relics to the government, mostly dating back to the Western Zhou
Dynasty (1100-771 B.C.)
</P>
<P>
The farmers are Bai Xinsi in Famen Township, and Qi Delin and
another who asked not be named in Huangdui Township. They
unearthed the relices while working in the fields.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists said that the cultural relics found by the
farmers include bronze mirrors and other kinds of bronze ware,
pottery and jade articles.
</P>
<P>
Weapons include daggers, swords and shields. Production
tools include axes.
</P>
<P>
Luo Xizhang, curator of the Zhouyuan Museum in Shaanxi
Province, said that the most precious relic is a bronze dagger
dating back 3000 years.
</P>
<P>
The dagger is 17.5 centimeters long. Its body is 13.5 cm long
and and its handle four cm long.  
</P>
</TEXT>
