<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Deploy 40,000 Troops During Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- A total of 40,000 members of
Bangladesh's armed forces will be deployed in the country to
ensure law and order during the June 12 parliamentary elections,
Chief Adviser to the caretaker government M. Habibur Rahman said
here today.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with members of the Overseas Correspondents
Association of Bangladesh, Habibur said the armed forces would be
deployed together with a large number of policemen and other
law-enforcing agencies.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the police have recovered 4,000 fire arms and a
huge quantity of explosives and ammunition since his caretaker
government took over power in early April.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, about 40,000 people have been arrested for
possession of illegal arms and on various criminal charges, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The chief adviser declined to comment on the demand for a
public trial of some detained army officers, including former
Chief of Army Staff A.S.M. Nasim, who are charged with a coup
attempt against the caretaker government.
</P>
<P>
"The whole thing is under investigation. Let us wait and see.
It is too early to make any comment," he said.
</P>
<P>
Nasim and six other senior army officers were sacked from their
posts and put under military custody on May 20 for alleged
involvement in a foiled mutiny.
</P>
<P>
The former largest opposition party, the Awami (People's)
League, has accused the Defense Ministry under President Abdur
Rahman Biswas of framing up the charges to serve a conspiracy of
the ex-ruling Bangladesh Nationalist Party to disrupt the coming
elections.
</P>
<P>
"Nothing is going to happen that will jolt the chances of a
free and fair election," the chief adviser said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the might of the people is behind the Election
Commission while all political parties have given their promises
of full cooperation.  
</P>
