<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Environmental Protection Official on White Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- A white paper China issued today
aims to enhance the understanding of its environmental protection
efforts by the international community.
</P>
<P>
 "Environmental Protection in China" will also promote
cooperation between China and the rest of the world, said a senior
environmental protection official today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, Xie Zhenhua, head of the State
Bureau of Environmental Protection, said China has, for the first
time in the form of a white paper, introduced to the international
community its environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
It is also the first time China has systematically and
scientifically summed up its achievements scored over the past 20
years, particularly since it launched its reform and opening to
the outside world, he said.
</P>
<P>
There has been misunderstandings in some foreign countries
about China's environmental protection measurers. Some countries
claimed that China had merely emphasized economic growth to the
neglect of environmental protection or its impact on people's
health, he said.
</P>
<P>
The white paper issued today has convinced the world that China
has taken all possible measures including legal, economic,
administrative, scientific and technological measures to protect
its environment, he said.
</P>
<P>
In the past 18 years, China's gross national product (GNP) has
grown by ten percent each year, but has avoided a deterioration in
the environment, he said.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the issue of the global environment, a few countries
blamed China for being a high pollution country, he said. The
white paper tells the world that China is a responsible nation,
which is striving to solve its own environmental problem.
</P>
<P>
Xie said China has drawn experience from the advanced countries
in environmental protection. But it has its own experiences and
distinctive environmental control technology.
</P>
<P>
"China can match the advanced countries in the administration
of environment protection," he said, adding that "the only
difference is that China lacks money and technology."
</P>
<P>
Xie also criticized some Western countries for paying only lip
service to solving global environmental issues since the United
Nations Environment And Development Conference in 1992.
</P>
<P>
"Few advanced countries have kept their promises to offer more
funds and technology for the solution to global environmental
issues," he said.
</P>
<P>
"As a large country, China will work hard to solve its
environmental issues. The effort itself is a contribution by China
to help solve the global environmental issues," Xie said, while
voicing his hope that the international community will support
and cooperate with China in the form of capital, technology and
experience. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
