<HEADLINE> Drive Launched to Learn Shijiazhuang's Model Taxi Drivers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Beijing taxi drivers have been
urged to go down the road of their colleagues in Shijiazhuang,
capital of north China's Hebei Province - by being more polite.
</P>
<P>
A forum was held in the Chinese capital to promote a nationwide
drive to encourage taxi drivers to have high moral conduct and be
still more polite and customer-friendly.
</P>
<P>
The event was held in Beijing's Great Hall of the People.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zhifeng, director of the Traffic Control Bureau of
Shijiazhuang city, introduced some of the city's model taxi
drivers, and spoke about the outstanding deeds they have peformed.
</P>
<P>
Shijiazhuang has 96 taxi companies, more than 4,800 taxis, and
over 9,600 taxi drivers, 85 percent of them self-employed.
</P>
<P>
Since December last year, the north China city launched
activities to improve the local taxi service trade in a bid to
combat impoliteness and rudeness by taxi drivers. Under attack
were drivers who failed to use their distance-meters, or refused
to take customers, overcharged, or spoke rudely to them.
</P>
<P>
Just half a year later the effort has helped the city's service
trade take on a new look and win public approval.
</P>
<P>
The forum was co-sponsored by the Ministry of Communications
and Hebei Province.  
</P>
</TEXT>
