<HEADLINE> Tutu Calls Buthelezi to End Boycott of Truth Body </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 4 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Truth and
Reconciliation Commission Chairman Archbishop Desmond Tutu today
held a 90-minute talk with Inkatha Freedom Party (IFP) leader
Mangosuthu Buthelezi, the South African Press Association
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held in Buthelezi's Ministerial Office in Cape
Town with the attendance of Deputy Commission Chairman Alex
Boraine and IFP Council member Joe Matthews.
</P>
<P>
The long-awaited meeting between Tutu and Buthelezi was the
last in a series which the commission had held with party leaders
to explain the aims and work of the 17-member panel which was
probing three decades of human rights abuses, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Buthelezi was the only major political leader not to have met
the commission since it was set up last December.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting, Tutu told Buthelezi it was crucial that
the truth commission hear IFP's side of the story on past human
rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
Buthelezi read out a prepared statement committing his party
to the ''notion of a nation-wide truth-finding exercise'', but
rejecting the structure of the commission as a ''recipe for great
evil''.
</P>
<P>
Buthelezi also criticised the 17-member panel appointed by
President Nelson Mandela, saying many commissioners were known to
have African National Congress (ANC) leanings.
</P>
<P>
''Just now the IFP leadership is still waiting with bated
breath as the ANC-led government has stated its intention to
charge some senior members of the IFP's national council,'' said
the IFP leader.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference after the meeting, Tutu repeatedly
emphasised the importance of the IFP appearing before the
commission.
</P>
<P>
Tutu said: ''Whatever the IFP may feel about the commission it
is important that their story must be told if we are going to
have a reasonable full account of the past conflict.''
</P>
<P>
Describing the meeting as ''full and frank'', tutu said he
still hoped the commission's display of independence and
even-handedness would persuade the IFP to drop its opposition to
the truth body.
</P>
<P>
However, Buthelezi said in his statement that the IFP doubted
whether the commission would be able to promote national unity
and reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
He also rejected the commission's powers to grant amnesty,
saying only the judiciary had the administrative capacity and the
skill to handle the amnesty applications in an objective and
technical fashion. enditem

=06041442

=06041443
NNNN
22:43 22:43 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
