<HEADLINE> ITU Approves New Standard for International Free-phone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The International Telecommunications
Union (ITU) approved on Tuesday a new standard to allocate phone
numbers for the international free-phone service.
</P>
<P>
Under the standard, subscribers of the service will be
allocated a unique Universal International Free-phone Number
(UIFN) which should be applied for and registered at the ITU
through telephone carriers, an ITU spokeswoman told reporters.
</P>
<P>
She added that the number, composed of a three digit country
code for global service application, then 800, then an eight-digit
global subscriber number, will be valid globally and subscribers
can retain it even if they change carriers.
</P>
<P>
The ITU will start to collect applications in December 1996 and
to assign UIFNs from February 1997.
</P>
<P>
"Free-phone" is a service which permits the cost of a telephone
call to be charged to the called party, rather than the calling
party.
</P>
<P>
Pioneered in the United States in 1966, the free-phone service
now carries around 100 million calls per day in the U.S. alone.
</P>
<P>
Free-phone has proved particularly popular with business
subscribers, who are often willing to bear the cost of a telephone
call in order to promote their services or to encourage customers
to order their products by phone.
</P>
<P>
Recent estimates by AT&AMP;T indicated some 100 billion
U.S. dollars is currently traded over the free-phone service every
year.
</P>
<P>
Until now, however, companies have been restricted by only
being able to use their free-phone number in one country. Those
who wish to offer services or products to customers abroad have no
choice but to register a separate number in each country, which
has proved unwieldy and often inefficient, the ITU said.
</P>
<P>
The ITU hoped that the new standard might stimulate the market
for free-phone services in Europe and the Asia-Pacific which until
now have been slow to take up the service, the spokeswoman added.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
