<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Announces Deregulation Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government today
announced a deregulation package to cut import duties, abolish
surcharges and streamline import regulations.
</P>
<P>
"The deregulatory measures aim to improve the competitive edge
of local products and are very consistent with the World Trade
Organization (WTO), the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC)
forum and the ASEAN Free Trade Areas (AFTA) regulations,"
Coordinating Minister for Production and Distribution Hartarto
told the press.
</P>
<P>
Coordinating Minister for Economy, Finance and Development
Supervision Saleh Afiff said the package covers 11 sectors,
including the rescheduling of import duty reduction, amendments to
import duties on capital goods and the abolition of surcharges.
</P>
<P>
Afiff said the new deregulation package sets a target of
cutting tariffs to 5 percent by the year 2000. Tariff reduction
will be carried out in 1997 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
For the export duty tariff, the government plans to cut the
rates in 1996, 1998 and 2000 to reach a target of 10 percent by
the year 2003.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government has so far reduced import duties of
1,497 out of 7,288 tariff items.
</P>
<P>
The deregulation also includes streamlining import regulations,
handling dumping charges, granting export facilities to exporters
planning to operate in certain sectors and simplifying procedures
for licensing industries to operate in industrial parks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
