<HEADLINE> Poors to benefit from Charitable Clinics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Charitable clinics have been
opened in six hospitals and sanatoriums in the capital of south
China's Guangdong Province to help impoverished families and
pensioners.
</P>
<P>
The Guangzhou Charity Society, the sponsor of the clinics,
handed out 40 free-health-care cards for families with low incomes
in each of the city's districts.
</P>
<P>
The society, which is one of the local organizations of the
China Charity Federation (CCF), will pay all the medical expenses
and clinic fees for the card-holders.
</P>
<P>
The CCF was established to promote charities and collect
donations. By the end of 1995, the CCF had recruited 44 local
organizations throughout the country as group members and it had
collected donations of over 100 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
A director at the Guangzhou Charity Society said that his
society is planning to build a charitable hospital this year.
</P>
