<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Indicates Milder Line on NATO Enlargement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny
Primakov today hinted that Moscow was not opposed to NATO
enlargement as such, but could not accept weapons and troops
being moved eastward.
</P>
<P>
He told the so-called "16 plus one meeting" with NATO foreign
ministers that a clear distinction should be drawn between the
military and political consequences of the enlargement.
</P>
<P>
At a short press conference after the meeting, Primakov called
his talks with the foreign ministers "very constructive," and said
it was important that the alliance was treating Russia as "a key
player" in the emerging security architecture in Europe.
</P>
<P>
"On our side, we believe that NATO is playing an important
role. It is adapting to the new realities," he said.
</P>
<P>
On his part, NATO Secretary General Javier Solana said "it is
our will not only to maintain but also to enlarge and deepen our
relations (with Russia)."
</P>
<P>
Primakov told the meeting that Moscow wants to start talks on a
tactical anti-missile defense system, as well as hold more regular
meetings with NATO members to start talks on an "enhanced
relationship," NATO sources said.
</P>
<P>
This dialogue could lead to a special relationship pact or
charter, which was proposed by NATO a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Russia has signaled recently that while it remains opposed to
NATO plans for eastward expansion, it realizes that the alliance
will eventually take in several countries in Central and Eastern
Europe.
</P>
<P>
Moscow's major concern, said diplomats, is to make sure that
the Baltic republics are not admitted to the alliance and that no
NATO troops or nuclear weapons are stationed on the soil of new
members.
</P>
<P>
A year ago, Russia signed the Partnership for Peace plan with
NATO, as well as a program for a broad and enhanced dialogue with
NATO beyond the plan.
</P>
<P>
Since then, no significant progress has been made on the
proposal for a special relationship with NATO to reflect Russia's
power, although Russian troops are serving with the NATO-led peace
Implementation Force in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
NATO foreign ministers agreed at a meeting on Monday that plans
to admit new members from Eastern Europe remained on track.
</P>
<P>
Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic are widely expected to
be the first countries to join the alliance, although no decisions
on "who and when" will be made before the end of this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
