<HEADLINE> Daya Bay N-Power Plant Operating to Full Capacity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Daya Bay Nuclear Power Plant
in south China's Guangdong Province has started to operate to full
capacity again.
</P>
<P>
The build up of energy output came after it completed the
second annual refueling and maintenance for its Unit 1 on May 31,
an official said today.
</P>
<P>
The Unit 1 shut down on March 31 for second refueling according
to schedule. Since then the plant has not only conducted regular
refueling and maintenance, but also replaced guide tubes of
control rods, said an official in charge of the plant.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the problem with the dropping time of
control rods in both units of the plant has been completely solved.
</P>
<P>
He also said that a damaged exciter in Unit 2 was transported
to Britain for repair a few months ago. After the repair work it
was installed in Unit 1 and has proved to be operating well.
</P>
<P>
Refueling and maintenance for Unit 2 ended in Mid-April. Both
generating units in the power plant are operating to full
capacity, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
