<HEADLINE> UN Investigates into Buffer Zone Killing in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Peace-Keeping Force in
Cyprus (UNFICYP) is investigating into the killing of an unarmed
Greek Cypriot soldier Monday in the U.N.-controlled buffer zone
and called for cooperation from both sides on the island to ensure
the security of the buffer zone.
</P>
<P>
An UNFICYP spokesman said today that "we continue to
investigate yesterday's killing and new elements are coming up."
</P>
<P>
The incident took place Monday morning when a Greek Cypriot
National Guardsman, Stelios Panagi, 19, entered unarmed the
U.N.-controlled buffer zone, for unknown reasons, at Ayios
Andreas area of Nicosia and the Turkish soldiers, who manned the
Turkish posts on the demarcation line fired shots at the Greek
Cypriot soldier.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. peacekeepers took the seriously wounded soldier to
the Nicosia General Hospital but the doctors there verified his
death.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the U.N. role in the incident, the spokesman
said it took the U.N. peace-keepers about 30 minutes before they
reached the body of the Greek Cypriot soldier, the eighth
National Guardsman killed by the Turks in the last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.N. resident representative Gustave Feissel said
today that "we are very saddened by this tragic incident and
useless loss of life of a young Greek Cypriot."
</P>
<P>
Feissel left this morning for Istanbul, Turkey to attend a
meeting Wednesday between U.N. Secretary-General Boutros
Boutros-Ghali, who is there on the occasion of a U.N. conference,
and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
Feissel said, "We are pursuing our investigation and I hope
that within a couple of days we will have completed it."
</P>
<P>
He said in the meantime, the UNFICYP commander has already met
with the Turkish force commander raising this matter "in very
strong terms". He will also meet the National Guard commander and
there will be further meetings with the Turkish commander.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official acknowledged that the U.N. force can not
control the whole of the buffer zone.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the cooperation of the two sides is
indispensable to ensure the security of the buffer zone and that
people from either side do not enter the buffer zone illegally.
</P>
<P>
After the incident, the Cyprus government has protested to the
U.N. and foreign governments over the killing of an unarmed Greek
Cypriot soldier.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides described the killing as "a
cold-blooded murder."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Greek Cypriot soldier entered the zone
unarmed and recalled that the incident had taken place within the
no man's land, which is under the U.N. control.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot south and the
Turkish Cypriot north since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded and
tool control of 37 percent of the island following an
Athens-backed coup.
</P>
<P>
The 1,200-strong U.N. peace-keeping force patrols the
180-kilometer long buffer zone across this east Mediterranean
island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
