<HEADLINE> Siemens to Invest 90m US Dollars in China's Power Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Germany's Siemens AG plans to
invest 1.1 billion US dollars in China by the turn of the century,
90 million US dollars of which will be poured into the country's
power industry.
</P>
<P>
Details of the investment plans were revealed at a meeting on
Siemens' instrumentation and control technology for power plants
held in Jiaxing Power Plant in east China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
China's power industry will witness a speedy development in the
coming years, increasing the country's demand for
electricity-generating equipment.
</P>
<P>
China is expected to add 10,000 megawatts of installed capacity
annually, providing a huge market for domestic and overseas
investors.
</P>
<P>
Siemens mainly provides electricity-generating equipment for
China's fossil-fueled as well as hydraulic power plants, and
process control systems for the country's fossil-fueled power
plants.
</P>
<P>
Siemens has already provided turbogenerators for fossil-fueled
power plants in Rizhao in Shandong province, in Hanfeng in Hebei
Province and in Yangshupu in Shanghai. And it also has provided
gas turbogenerators for the Yangpu Power Plant in Hainan Province,
and hydraulic electrogenerators for some water power plants.
</P>
<P>
It has also won orders to provide two sets of 350,000 kw of
units for Fuzhou Power Plant in southeast Fujian Province and six
sets of 350,000 kw of units for Yangcheng Power Plant in north
China's Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The company will also invest more than 100 million German Marks
to join the Dongfang Group in Chengdu in southwest China's Sichuan
Province to set up a joint venture to produce
electricity-generating equipment.
</P>
<P>
Siemens now has two joint ventures in China to produce process
control systems -- Teleperm, one in Nanjing and the other in
Dalian.
</P>
<P>
The Jiaxing Power Plant has used the control systems for its
two sets of 300,000 kw of units. The plant plans to add six sets
of 600,000 kw of units for its second phase of expansion.
</P>
<P>
Siemens hopes to get new orders for the control systems from
the Jiaxing Power Plant for its second phase of expansion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
