<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smoking in Public Places Banned in Shantou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANTOU, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Another Chinese city has decided to
impose a no-smoking ban in public places.
</P>
<P>
The government of Shantou, Guangdong Province has joined a
number of other Chinese cities including Beijing, Shanghai and
Guangzhou in banning smoking in public places.
</P>
<P>
The Provisional Regulations of the Shantou Special Economic
Zone on Banning Smoking in public places state that people who
smoke in auditoriums, meeting halls, classrooms, buses, clinics,
cinemas, theaters, libraries, stadiums or any other public place
will be fined five yuan.
</P>
<P>
A national survey conducted in 1991 shows that 56.8 percent of
males over the age of 15 in Shantou smoke cigarettes, three
percentage points higher than the nation's average.
</P>
<P>
The city government has organized 8,000 people to make sure
that the no-smoking order is carried out in public places.
</P>
</TEXT>
