<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Breeding Ground of Black-beaked Gull Discovered in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Eggs of a rare gull have been
discovered in a Chinese deer protection zone.
</P>
<P>
A total of 26 eggs of black-beaked gull were spotted in a
polder area of Dafeng County, east China's Jiangsu province.
</P>
<P>
The discovery has proved that the David's deer protection zone
in the polder area in Dafeng County, where these eggs were found,
is one of the few breeding places of black-beaked gulls in the
world.
</P>
<P>
Black-beaked gull, not well known by people, is a rare bird in
the world, described as a small-sized gull.
</P>
<P>
River mouth areas in China's Hainan island and Zhanjiang city
of southern China's Guangdong province are habitats for
black-beaked gull in winter. There are also traces the gulls in
beach areas in the Republic of Korea, Japan, Taiwan and other
countries and regions worldwide.
</P>
<P>
During spring, their traces are usually found in beach areas of
Beidaihe in north China's Hebei province and seaside of
Vladivostok, Russia. But the number of black-beaked gulls found in
those places only stands at 30 to 40.
</P>
<P>
The polder area in Dafeng county has favorable conditions for
breeding black-beaked gulls, with the establishment of protection
zones in the area and improvement of environmental conditions.
</P>
<P>
Some 30 varieties of rare wildlife under state protection have
been found in the area. Varieties of birds in the area have risen
to 315 from 184 ten years ago.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
