<HEADLINE> Iraqi Oil Minister Leaves for OPEC Meeting in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Oil Minister Amir Mohammed
Rashid left here Monday evening for Vienna to attend the
ministerial conference of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC) due to start Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The OPEC meeting will concentrate on the study of the new oil
situation in the world following the signing of the oil-for-food
deal between Iraq and the United Nations on May 20.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi newspaper al-Jumhuriyah today quoted foreign news
agency dispatches as saying that the OPEC preparatory meeting has
concluded with the easing of concerns over a possible declining in
oil price in the world market once Iraq reenters it.
</P>
<P>
Oil exports present at the preparatory meeting said that the
oil production quota for Iraq must be under control but Iraq
insisted that its oil production quota of 3.14 million barrels
per day before August 1990 should be maintained.
</P>
<P>
Rashid said last week that the OPEC production quota for Iraq
should be adhered to and that other oil producers should not share
the quota saved by Iraq due to the U.N. oil and trade sanctions
imposed after Iraqi troops invaded Kuwait in August 1990.
</P>
<P>
Iraq will support for any "constructive" negotiations at the
forthcoming OPEC conference which will contribute to a stable
world price, Rashid added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
