<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bigger Transactions on China's Inter-bank Lending Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 4 (Xinhua) -- China raised more than 71 billion
yuan in fund-raising centers nationwide in May, up about 43.68
percent over April.
</P>
<P>
Outside the fund-raising centers, Chinese banks raised 18 or so
billion yuan, up some 53 percent from April and non-bank financial
institutions mustered about 11.8 billion yuan, up about a quarter
from the previous month.
</P>
<P>
On the inter-bank lending markets, transactions in the 60-day
lending expanded dramatically to 15.482 billion yuan, accounting
for 30.5 percent of the total turnover, of which 50.54 percent was
attributed to lendings with maturity of more than one month.
</P>
<P>
Trading in the seven-day and 30-day lendings were also active.
</P>
<P>
Analysts pointed out that for most of the time in May interest
rates on all inter-bank lendings were stable and lower than in
April, fluctuating between 0.95 percent to 1.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
But interest rate on the seven-day lending dropped to 0.735
percent on May 20, a record low since the national inter-bank
lending market was launched five months ago. Average interest
rates on 30-day-plus lendings, however, hit 1.155 percent.
</P>
<P>
Average weighted interest rate was 0.958 percent on the
seven-day lending, 0.971 percent on the 20-day lending, 0.988
percent on the 30-day lending, 1.07 percent of the 60-day lending,
1.13 percent on the 90-day lending, and 1.17 percent on the
120-day lending.
</P>
<P>
During the 22 trading days in May, the Shanghai-based China
Foreign Exchange Trading System had a turnover totaling 50.5085
billion yuan, 42.74 percent more than in April.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Global FDI Flows in 1995 Surge to All-Time High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Worldwide foreign direct investment
(FDI) flows surged to an all-time high in 1995, but the developing
South still received a much smaller share of the total FDI than
the developed North, latest U.N. data said.
</P>
<P>
The global FDI flows were estimated at 325 billion U.S. dollars
in 1995, a 46 percent rise over 1994, preliminary U.N. Conference
on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) data released Tuesday showed.
</P>
<P>
Following their emergence from a period of slow growth and
boosted by a new wave of mergers and acquisitions, FDI inflows to
the developed countries reached an estimated 216 billion dollars
in 1995. The United States led the way with record inflows of 75
billion and record outflows of 97 billion.
</P>
<P>
Developing countries registered an estimated 97 billion in FDI
inflows, a record high. And the transitional economies of Central
and Eastern Europe received twice as much FDI in 1995 as in 1994,
an estimated 12 billion, also the highest figure on record.
</P>
<P>
The UNCTAD pointed out that both in developing countries and
Central and Eastern Europe, a small number of countries accounted
for a large part of the increases in FDI inflows: China,
Indonesia, Malaysia and Thailand in the former group and the Czech
Republic, Hungary, and Russia in the latter group.
</P>
<P>
According to UNCTAD analysis, the unprecedented level of global
FDI flows in 1995 suggests that the speed of globalization of
production by trans-national corporations may be accelerating.
</P>
<P>
Extensive data and analysis of the 1995 global FDI flows will be
provided by the UNCTAD in its annual World Investment Report to be
published at the end of the year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Likely to Lift Mad Cow Derivatives Ban on Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The EU Commission said it would
lift a worldwide ban on British beef derivatives after EU farm
ministers failed to come to a decision on the issue Monday night,
local radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture ministers of the 15 EU countries voted 9-6 in favor
of easing the ban on gelatine, tallow and bull semen at a meeting
in Luxembourg Monday night. But under EU voting rules, six votes
against were enough to block the decision.
</P>
<P>
Under EU rules, the issue will automatically go to the EU
Commission.
</P>
<P>
EU farm commissioner Franz Fischler told reporters that the
Commission will lift the ban.
</P>
<P>
"We will now go ahead and lift the ban," he said.
</P>
<P>
Germany, Portugal, Austria, the Netherlands, Belgium and
Luxembourg voted against easing the ban Monday night.
</P>
<P>
The EU Commission ordered a worldwide ban on the export of
British cows, beef and beef derivatives on March 27 after mad cow
disease, or Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy, was linked to its
human equivalent, Creutzfeld-Jakob Disease.
</P>
<P>
The EU Commission on May 21 formally asked the Council of
Agricultural Ministers to decide on the partial lift of the ban.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister John Major demanded the same day that the
EU lift the derivatives ban and then set a framework for a
complete end to the overall beef embargo.
</P>
<P>
He also threatened to block all EU decisions that require
unanimity if the EU fails to meet his demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greater Zhuhai-Macao Technological Cooperation Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHUHAI, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Zhuhai Special Economic Zone
enjoys bright prospects for scientific and technological
cooperation with Macao, according to a local official.
</P>
<P>
Chen Jingping, deputy director of the Zhuhai High-Tech
Industrial Development Zone Administrative Commission, said,
"Macao's economy has been growing rapidly in the past few years."
</P>
<P>
Macao has formed an industrial structure focusing on
export-oriented processing, tourism, real estate, construction,
finance and insurance, he said,
</P>
<P>
He said the export-oriented processing industry has become the
foundation of Macao's economy, but is still characterized by
labor-intensive operations.
</P>
<P>
The industry also suffers from such problems as rising
production costs and the shortage of researchers.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that Zhuhai has become a major center for expanding
high-tech industries in Guangdong Province after ten years of
construction.
</P>
<P>
Flexible policies are being pursued in Zhuhai to encourage
investors from Macao and overseas.
</P>
<P>
"The Zhuhai High-Tech Industrial Development Zone has created a
fine investment environment since its establishment three years
ago," he said.
</P>
<P>
Prices of raw materials, labor, land and workshop buildings in
the zone are far lower than those in Macao, he said.
</P>
<P>
The zone has forged long-term research cooperation relations
with 36 key universities and colleges, military factories and
research institutes in other parts of the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
But though it has a large technical work force, it lacks funds,
he added.
</P>
<P>
"I think Zhuhai and Macao can supply each other's needs,
greatly expand cooperation in science and technology research and
development and jointly build new high-tech industries," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation will help Macao upgrade its industrial structure,
enable it to turn out goods with a high added value and increase
the competitiveness of its products on the global market, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
He proposed that Zhuhai should focus on developing and
manufacturing high-tech products in his zone, while Macao should
concentrate on packing and marketing such products.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
