The meeting was attended by the German, French, British,
U.S. and Russian foreign ministers, representatives from the EU
troika (Spain, Italy and Ireland) and the European Commission, and
Carl Bildt, the EU's highest civilian administrator in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the Contact Group welcomed the joint
declaration issued in Geneva on Sunday by Presidents Alija
Izetbegovic of Bosnia, Slobodan Milosevic of Serbia and Franjo
Tudjman of Croatia.
</P>
<P>
The declaration called the conduct of free and fair elections
in Bosnia by the September 14 deadline the most important
follow-on step in the peace process. The election deadline is
stipulated in the Dayton peace agreement on Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The statement said a "serious obstacle" in the way of the
election process were persons indicted by the International
Criminal Tribunal on the Former Yugoslavia who are still holding
high-ranking official positions.
</P>
<P>
It said: "The parties are obliged to respect the interdiction
according to which individuals indicted of war crimes by the
Tribunal must not strive for or hold any public office, no matter
whether it was conferred upon them or obtained through elections."
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the Bosnia arms control negotiations under the
aegis of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe
are "indispensable" for comprehensive peace and regional stability
in Bosnia, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
It called upon the parties concerned to complete these
negotiations by June 6 as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
The participants at today's meeting also agreed to hold the
next ministerial-level meeting this summer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
