<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museum Attracts More Visitors at Weekends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of people in Nanjing have
been taking a cut-price visit into China's cultural history.
</P>
<P>
The Nanjing Museum in the capital of east China's Jiangsu
Province has been attracting more local residents since it halved
its admission price, especially during the weekend work breaks.
</P>
<P>
With a collection of 420,000 exhibits, the museum started the
low-price ticket system on April 1. Local people can visit the
museum at a price as half as before during the weekend.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the museum is free to primary and middle
school students, members of the armed services, outstanding
workers, seniors over 60 years old, and the handicapped people.
</P>
<P>
The museum is the third largest museum in China following the
Beijing Palace Museum and Taipei Palace Museum. It has held dozens
of historic, archaeological and collection exhibitions since 1985.
</P>
<P>
The exhibitions includes an amethyst tea pots exhibition,
exhibition of ancient pottery and porcelain, exhibition of ancient
women's garments and ornaments, exhibition of 5,000-year
civilization of the Yangtze River Low Reaches, and displays of
archaeological discoveries.
</P>
<P>
Xu Huping, deputy curator of the museum, said that the low
ticket price has attracted thousands of visitors especially during
the weekends.
</P>
<P>
"Free exhibitions for pupils will help them learn more about
the country's culture in ancient times," said a primary teacher.
</P>
</TEXT>
