<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Ministry Spokesman on NATO's Reform Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- China expressed the hope today that
proposed reforms by the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)
would benefit peace and stability in Europe and the rest of the
world.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on an agreement to reform the NATO reached by
foreign ministers of the member countries on Monday, Chinese
Foreign Ministry spokesman Shen Guofang said that NATO is "a
product of the cold war."
</P>
<P>
"In the wake of the cold war, NATO has taken a series of
self-adjustments to cope with the new circumstances and is still
in the process of reforming itself," Shen said at a press
conference in Beijing this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, Shen said, it is inevitable to re-adjust the
relationship between Europe and the United States within the
framework of NATO.
</P>
<P>
"This also shows that it is becoming increasingly impossible
for any single force to dominate European affairs
single-handedly," he said.
</P>
<P>
There is no relationship between China and the Nato, Shen
noted. However, he added, "we hold that actions taken by NATO
should conform to the security interests and aspirations of the
relevant countries and regions and also benefit peace and
stability in Europe and the world as a whole." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
