<HEADLINE> Suspended Athlete Could Compete in Olympic Trials: Judge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 4 (Xinhua) -- A federal judge in Pheonix, the
United States, on Monday has extended a court injunction allowing
banned heptathlete Gea Johnson to compete in the national Olympic
trials.
</P>
<P>
Johnson, who was suspended for four years in 1994 following a
positive doping test for steroid by the International Amateur
Athletic Federation and USA Track and Field, was suing the two
bodies for 12 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The trials will begin on June 14 in Atlanta, where Johnson will
compete in the heptathlon, in which the top three qualify for the
Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
U.S. District Judge Earl Carroll accepted jurisdiction in the
case, in which Johnson alleged that her doping test was mishandled.
</P>
<P>
Carroll also ordered DNA testing on the positive urine sample
to identify whether it was Johnson's and wanted the report to be
submitted by July 10.
</P>
<P>
He said the next court hearing will be held on July 22, three
days after the Olympics' opening ceremony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
