<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TCM to Boom in Next Fifteen Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Traditional Chinese medicine (TCM)
industry is expected to produce 36 billion yuan by the year 2000,
with an annual growth rate of 15 percent during the next five
years, said a senior health official.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhang Wenkang, Director of the State
Administration of Traditional Chinese Medicine (SATCM), the output
of TCM will reach 110 billion yuan by the year 2010. By the end of
this century, he said, China will have 15 large and 40
average-sized TCM enterprises with an annual output of more than
100 million yuan, reported today's People's Daily (Overseas
Edition).
</P>
<P>
International involvement with TCM should be expanded to open
the world market to China's TCM products, he said, adding that
export volume of TCM is expected to rise to 800 million US dollars
by the year 2000, and to two billion US dollars by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
The percentage of TCM clinical service at hospitals affiliated
with the Ministry of Public Health should amount to 30 percent by
the year 2,000 and 40 percent by 2,010, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
He said that 80 percent of the urban TCM hospitals and clinics
and 60 percent of the rural TCM hospitals and clinics should offer
comprehensive services for treatment, prevention of illness,
recovery and health care.
</P>
<P>
The wards for TCM divisions should cover five percent of the
total space at the country's comprehensive hospitals.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
