<HEADLINE> Philippines to Increase Infrastructure Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
increase infrastructure spending for the continual expansion of
the economy, according to the government's Memorandum on Economic
and Financial Policies (MEFP) available today.
</P>
<P>
The MEFP, to be submitted to the International Monetary Fund
(IMF), said "capital spending needs to be stepped up to address
the large backlog of unmet infrastructure needs."
</P>
<P>
On the basis of a recent review of the Philippine economy by an
IMF team, the MEFP acknowledged that Manila needs to focus its
structural efforts on securing additional revenues in the coming
years.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, multilateral financial institutions such as the Asian
Development Bank and the World Bank had voiced concern over the
country's problems in infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
In the Asian region, an average of about 5 to 9 percent of the
gross national product (GNP) is allocated to infrastructure
projects.
</P>
<P>
However, in the Philippines, the allocation accounts for only 3
to 4 percent of the GNP, in spite of the government's efforts to
ease the funding requirement for the infrastructure projects
through build-operate-transfer schemes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
