<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Unifies Property Service Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital unified its
property service charges in all residential areas as of June 1.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time a Chinese city has standardized service
charges.
</P>
<P>
The move should improve management in the local real estate
sector and regulate the service charges in an orderly way,
according to Beijing Evening News.
</P>
<P>
Newly-standardized charges will cover services such as wastes
transport, security, and the collecting of electricity, water,
rent and parking fees in the public residential areas.
</P>
<P>
Those who own commodity houses also should pay fees for
elevator and television wire services.
</P>
<P>
It is illegal for property management companies to increase or
lower the services charges, and those who violate the rule will be
punished and fined.
</P>
<P>
China plans to invest 236 billion yuan (28.4 billion US
dollars) on the construction of commodity housing in the coming
five years. The management of these houses has been problematic,
sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
