<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Cuts Water Supply Budget by Two Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Beijing is to cut its water supply
by two percent this year to relieve the city's water shortage
caused by drought.
</P>
<P>
The industrial sector will face a 2.07 percent cut, hotels and
restaurants by 2.92 percent, colleges and universities by two
percent, hospitals by 1.58 percent and other fields by 2.66
percent.
</P>
<P>
Units fined for wasting water in 1995 will have their water
supplies reduced by two to 15 percent, according to the "Beijing
Youth Daily".
</P>
<P>
Experts said this move is due to the fact that Beijing's per
capita annual water supply has dropped from 400 cubic meters to
300, constituting only one-thirteenth of the world's average, or
one-seventh of the nation's average, or 20 percent less than
Israel's average.
</P>
<P>
The city faced its fourth major drought, since 1950s, during
the period between last winter and this spring, when its rainfall
was only 12.2 mm, 18.9 mm less than the same 1995 period.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this April 16 local reservoirs held 3.739 billion
cubic meters of water, 120 million cubic meters less than the same
1995 period.
</P>
<P>
More than 22 percent of the city's machine wells do not have
enough water, and some even refuse to supply water.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government has vowed to make every effort to save
water, make full use of water and fight any kind of waste of
water. Water supplies for local primary and middle schools, and
some key sectors and industries are guaranteed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
