<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1,000 Franchisers to Gain Foothold in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- At least 1,000 foreign and local
franchisers are expected to gain foothold in the Philippine market
by the year 2000, creating jobs for some one million Filipinos,
the Philippine Franchise Association (PFA) predicted today.
</P>
<P>
At the Philippine International Franchise Conference here
today, PFA President Samie Lim said franchising is expected to
become one of the country's biggest foreign exchange earners in
the next five years.
</P>
<P>
There are already 200 foreign and local franchisers in the
country at present, Lim noted.
</P>
<P>
He said franchising is a business option to local retailers in
the liberalized retail industry.
</P>
<P>
Also at the conference, Mark Siebert, president of Francorp
Inc., the world's largest franchise development consulting firm,
projected a robust growth in the franchising business in the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
A PFA study showed that there were 64 local businesses in
various franchising stages and formats in the country in 1995.
</P>
<P>
According to the PFA, as of the first quarter of 1996, an
additional 30 businesses, in both food and non-food sectors, have
adopted franchising as a method of expansion in the Philippines.
</P>
</TEXT>
