<HEADLINE> Mahathir Tells West to Mind Their Own Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad today criticized the West for interfering other's
internal affairs, saying that the Malaysian people do not need
others to tell them how the country should be run.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after officially launching the "World Consumers Day
1996" here today, Mahathir said: "Who are they to determine how
our people should live? This is our country, so we are the one to
decide."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on an assessment by a Germany-based group,
Transparency International, which ranked Malaysia the 26th most
corrupt country out of 50 states surveyed, Mahathir said such
group still had strong colonial mentality.
</P>
<P>
"I can't understand this mentality," Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
He said the West should look at racial discrimination and
corruption in Europe which was very high there, and pointed out
that the worst record of human rights violation was to be found in
Europe today.
</P>
<P>
He said the West has always interfered in other country's
internal affairs, adding: "We have to tell them stop telling us
what to do." Mahathir concluded with the words: "Mind your own
business!"  
</P>
