<HEADLINE> First American Oil Company Opens Business in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, June 4 (Xinhua) -- A major American oil company,
Caltex, opened its first retail station here today after a 20-year
absence.
</P>
<P>
Caltex is the first American oil company to enter the petroleum
retail business in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
John Raeside, general manager of the Caltex Cambodia Limited,
told reporters that Caltex plans to invest 20 million U.S. dollars
in Cambodia in the coming years to build a supply and distribution
system and a retail network of 20 petrol stations in Phnom Penh
and other regions.
</P>
<P>
Caltex will take nearly 10 percent of Cambodia's oil market in a
few years, Raeside said.
</P>
<P>
At the heart of Caltex's investment is a marine terminal at
Sihanoukville scheduled for completion by mid 1997, he said.
</P>
<P>
High-quality products at internationally competitive prices
will be imported through the terminal from Caltex's refineries in
Singapore and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia consumes 11,000 barrels of oil daily and 650,000 tons
a year.
</P>
<P>
Caltex, a 50/50 joint venture between two major American
multinationals -- Chevron Corp. and Texaco Inc., is one of the
largest producers of petroleum products in the Asia-Pacific
region. It plans to invest up to 8 billion dollars over the next
five years, mainly in the Asia-Pacific region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
