<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 100 Million Homeless in World: UN Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISTANBUL, June 4 (Xinhua) -- About 100 million people in the
world are homeless, most of them women and dependent children,
says Wally N'Dow, Secretary General of the Second United Nations
Conference on Human Settlements (HABITAT II).
</P>
<P>
A written statement released today by the U.N. Center for
Human Settlements based in Nairobi, Kenya, points out that the
problem is not just homeless. Overall, at least 600 million
people live in shelters that are life-threatening or
health-threatening in developing world cities.
</P>
<P>
Every day, some 50,000 people, mostly women and children, die
as a result of poor shelter, polluted water and inadequate
sanitation, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The main reason for homelessness among women and their
dependent children is poverty," says N'Dow, who is also Assistant
Secretary General and head of HABITAT.
</P>
<P>
"Women are doubly disadvantaged by their need to earn a living
while providing care for family members and running households,"
the report quoted N'Dow as saying.
</P>
<P>
Of the estimated 1.3 billion people living in poverty around
the world, 70 percent are women and girls. Women and girls are
also the fastest increasing group of impoverished, a process
called "the global feminization of poverty."
</P>
<P>
The United Nations estimates that if all housing could be
brought to a minimum acceptable standard, there would be 5
million fewer deaths and 2 million fewer permanent disabilities
annually on a global basis.
</P>
<P>
The two-week HABITAT II, also called "City Summit," started
Monday in Istanbul, Turkey, with the participation of government
and non-government organization representatives from some 150
countries.
</P>
<P>
The global conference is aimed at finding solutions to urban
problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
