<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Johnson Claims Taken Hostage in Ghana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 4 (Xinhua) -- One of Liberia's warring faction
leaders, Roosevelt Johnson, has claimed the Ghanian government
was holding him in Accra against his will.
</P>
<P>
"I think there is some game being played here" said the
general who has been staying in the Ghanian capital ever since
the failed west African summit meeting in early May aimed at
resolving the fresh round of armed conflict in the Liberian
capital.
</P>
<P>
"It looks like there is some deal to get rid of me so that
Taylor will walk over our people in Monrovia," Johnson was quoted
as saying by a report reaching here today. His troops have been
fighting with the men loyal to Charles Taylor, another warlord of
Liberia.
</P>
<P>
Monrovia has calmed down since last week when the African
peacekeeping forces, ECOMOG, declared that they had taken full
control of the city and the warring factions had stopped fighting
and began to withdraw from the capital.
</P>
<P>
Johnson was evacuated on May 4 from Monrovia to the Sierra
Leonian capital of Freetown by the United States marines. A
Ghanian aircraft flew him to Accra to atttend the May 7-8
emergency summit of the West African Committee of Nine on
Liberia.
</P>
<P>
"They assured us they were going to take us back. But they are
dodging us and refusing to take us back to Monrovia," said
Johnson, adding that his local and international telephone lines
had all been cut.
</P>
<P>
"This is a deliberate attempt to hold us hostage," said the
angry Johnson.
</P>
<P>
When asked to comment on the matter, Ghana's Deputy Foreign
Minister Mohamed Chambas said: "We advised Johnson that there is
no point in his rushing back to Monrovia until the ruling council
of state has met and taken certain decisions."
</P>
<P>
"Now if he disagrees with that, that is not helpful to the
peace process in Liberia," said Chambas.
</P>
<P>
The Ghanian official said that Johnson, who had already issued
the statement recommitting himself to the Abuja peace accord
signed last August as demanded by the west African mediators,
would be allowed to return as soon as the Liberian authority
reinstate him as the local government minister.
</P>
<P>
The Liberian council of state was set up according to the
Abuja peace agreement which set August 20, 1996 as the date for
the general elections in the west African country torn apart by
over six years of civil war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Ministers Meet Primakov on Improving Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Berlin, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Ministers of the 16 NATO
member countries met early this morning with their Russian
counterpart, Yevgeny Primakov, in Berlin in a bid to improve
NATO-Russia relations.
</P>
<P>
NATO sources said there were signs that Moscow might be willing
to improve ties despite its continued objection to NATO's eastward
expansion.
</P>
<P>
"There are some good signs... Primakov has said he would like
regular contacts," said a NATO official.
</P>
<P>
Russia has signalled recently that while it still opposes NATO
plans on eastward expension, it realizes that the alliance will
eventually take in several countries in central and eastern
Europe.
</P>
<P>
Moscow's major concern, said diplomats, is to make sure the
Baltic republics are not admitted and that no NATO troops or
nuclear weapons be stationed on the land of its new members.
</P>
<P>
A year ago, Russia signed the PfP (Partnership for Peace)
Individual Partnership Program with NATO, as well as a program for
a broad, enhanced dialogue with NATO beyond PfP.
</P>
<P>
Since then no major progress has been made on the promise of a
special relationship with NATO to reflect Russia's power, although
Russian troops are serving with the NATO-led peace force in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Primakov was due to lunch with U.S. Secretary of State Warren
Christopher on Tuesday, on the sidelines of the ministerial
meeting of the North Atlantic Cooperation Council which brings
together NATO members with their former Warsaw Pact foes.
</P>
<P>
NATO foreign ministers agreed at a meeting on Monday that plans
to take in new members from Eastern Europe remained in track.
</P>
<P>
Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic are widely expected to
be in the first wave, although no decisions on "who and when" will
be made before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Before the NATO meeting with Primakov, foreign ministers from
the five-nation "Contact Group" of major powers which coordinate
policy on Bosnia met to review the prospects for the country's
first post-war elections.
</P>
<P>
No details of the contact group meeting were immediately
available.
</P>
<P>
However, it was agreed on Monday by the 16 NATO foreign
ministers that NATO force in Bosnia would not start withdrawing
until after the elections in September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
