<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Sunken Ship Becomes Permanent Tomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's sunken ship "MV
Bukoba", which capsized with over 600 passengers, has become a
permanent tomb for those "lost at sea", "The Guardian" of the
east African country reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report came after a symbolic burial ceremony was held
yesterday at the scene of the accident in Lake Victoria.
</P>
<P>
The joint service was held aboard four vessels -- MV Butiama,
Clarias, Ukerewe and Orion, each carrying about 250 mouners.
</P>
<P>
The government was represented by chief justice Francis
Nyalali, who shoved a handful of sand into the lake as a burial
symbol.
</P>
<P>
The government has called off the rescue operation because of
possible health hazard caused by the bodies buried 27 metres at
the bottom of the lake. The bodies are said to have decomposed
beyond recognition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
