<HEADLINE> Malaysia Agrees to Assist Laos In Various Fields </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia agreed here today
that it would help Laos develop its agriculture, tourism and civil
aviation to further expand their bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference after the inaugural
Malaysia-Laos Joint Commission meeting here today, Malaysian
Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi said Malaysia would help
Laos reforest 120,000 hectares of land.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said Malaysia would also help Laos develop
broadcasting, telecommunications and hydropower infrastructure in
the land-locked state which is set to join the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) next year.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia would support Laos' proposal to build a rail
link between Vientiane and Bangkok, which will make Laos more
accessible.
</P>
<P>
Laotian Foreign Minister Somsavat Lengsavat, who headed the
Laotian delegation at the meeting, also told the press conference:
"Laos has vast land but we don't have enough data on land survey
and utilization of land."
</P>
<P>
He also asked Malaysia for assistance in aquaculture and crop
cultivation including rubber and oil palm.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers said both sides will step up
cooperation in tourism, adding Malaysia Airlines will begin
twice-weekly flights to Vientiane via Phnom Penh from July 1 this
year.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, the two foreign ministers witnessed the signing
of a memorandum of understanding on the establishment of the
Malaysia-Laos Joint Commission.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
