<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Trade Volume Sharply Increased </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam is expecting to earn an
export turn-over worth 3.05 billion U.S. dollars in the first half
of this year, a 16.5 percent increase compared with the same
period last year while its import will be valued at 4.8 billion
U.S. dollars, report here said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's import-export turnover has shown a sharp rise, with
an average increase of 20 percent in exports and 22 percent in
imports per year for a decade now, especially since 1991. This is
nearly three times faster than the annual gdp growth rate.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam now has trade ties with 104 countries and its essential
export items have increased from two before 1991 to 12 at present,
including crude oil, rice, marine products, textiles and garments,
coffee, rubber, cashew and other farm products.
</P>
<P>
Garments are top on the list of most increased export articles,
registering an annual rise of 30-40 percent. Now, the country has
more than 3,000 garment companies and enterprises employing tens
of thousands of young workers.
</P>
<P>
Different from the previous years, report said, the first half
of this year sees an immense decline in the import of foreign
consumer goods which have represented only 10 percent compared to
the corresponding period last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
