<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taliban Rejects Rabbani's Offer For Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Islamic militia
Taliban has rejected an offer for peace talks by President
Burhanuddin Rabbani, and again demanded his resignation.
</P>
<P>
According to a report reaching here today from the Afghan
capital of Kabul, the Taliban said the offer was based on "mala
fide intentions."
</P>
<P>
The Taliban also said on Monday that the Kabul regime had
carried out eight attacks on it since Rabbani reached a patch-up
with Hezb-i-Islami of Gulbadin Hikmatyar.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Monday, Rabbani said at a press conference that he
was ready to renegotiate the recently concluded power-sharing deal
with Hekmatyar if his key rivals decide to join the government,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani renewed his offer to the Taliban and General Abdul
Rashid Dostam, urging them to join the intra-Afghan dialogue aimed
at broadening the base of his government.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani said he had sent a "goodwill" delegation to Dostam's
headquarters in Mazar-i-Sharif, and another government team would
be sent to southwestern Kandahar for talks with the Taliban
leadership.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, which has been besieging Kabul for more than eight
months, have so far refused to hold talks with the Rabbani
government, dubbing his administration as "corrupt and
un-Islamic".
</P>
<P>
Dostam, whose National movement controls several northern
provinces, has also rejected similar offers in the past.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
