<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xi'an-Istanbul Camel Expedition Embarks on "Silk Road" Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Xi'an, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Three Turks, one American, and their
two Chinese guides on Sunday began a camel expedition from Xi'an,
capital of northwest China's Shaanxi Province, to Istanbul in
Turkey, along the ancient "silk road."
</P>
<P>
The group of photographers will journey to Turkey over the next
18 months to film local conditions and customs along the ancient
roadway. They are expected to cover 18,000 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
They will travel to Istanbul via Lanzhou (in China's
Gansu Province), Turpan and Kuqa (in Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region), Kirghizstan, Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan and Turkmenistan.
</P>
<P>
Such long marches by camel were common 1,000 years ago, when
world silk trade was flourishing, but such a trip is rare today.
</P>
<P>
The travelers received an official send-off in Xi'an from
hundreds of local citizens as well as Berhan Ekinci, the Turkish
Ambassador to China, who came from the Chinese capital of Beijing,
and Zhang Fuchun, Vice-Mayor of Xi'an.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
