<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO -- A Japanese warship has mistakenly shot down a
U.S. fighter jet during naval exercises in the Pacific Ocean off
Hawaii Tuesday, a Defense Agency official was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korean President Kim Young-sam nominated Kim
Soo-han of the ruling New Korea Party (NKP) as National Assembly
speaker Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
President Kim, who heads the ruling party, also named Oh
Se-eung vice National Assembly speaker, NKP spokesman Kim Chul
announced here.
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The European Union (EU) Tuesday urged Germany to
lower its budget deficit to meet conditions for its switch to an
EU-wide single currency system.
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- An outbreak of dengue fever, a cholera-like
disease, in Indonesia's 27 provinces has killed 117 people and
hospitalized more than 5,000 others over the past five months, a
senior health official was quoted as saying today.
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Bosnian Serbs today appealed to
the Bosnian Muslim-Croat Federation to release 1,300 prisoners of
war and 1,000 civilians who the Serbs claimed were still held
captive by the Muslims and Croats.
</P>
<P>
Momir Talic, commander of the Bosnian Serb military forces
around Banjaluka, made the appeal while meeting with Michael
Jackson, commander of the southwestern district of the NATO-led
multinational peacekeeping force, and Pierre Kraehenbuhl, chief of
the International Red Cross delegation to Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The United Nations has called for 80 million
U.S. dollars in aid to cover both humanitarian activities and the
operation of a 138-member U.N. monitor contingent in Iraq, a
U.N. spokesman said Tuesday. 
</P>
