<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 09:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Media Critical of Likud's Threats of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Israeli media have expressed
their grave concerns over Likud's threats to "settle accounts" for
their alleged negative reporting of the Likud election campaign.
</P>
<P>
Likud member of the Knesset (parliament) Limor Livnat, ticked
to be the new communications minister, lashed out today at the
media for their hostility against Likud during the election
campaign, adding she will propose the privatization of the Israeli
Broadcasting Association (IBA).
</P>
<P>
Privatizing the IBA means laying off at least half of its
staff, but Livnat denied any link between Likud's grievance and
the privatizing proposal.
</P>
<P>
"There is no reason for it to continue existing at the public
expense. Our philosophy is that all state-owned enterprises ought
to be privatized, and the IBA is just another one of them," she
said.
</P>
<P>
Criticizing the electronic media, Livnat singled out the
Channel 1 Television for its "attitude of unmitigated
discrimination against the Likud."
</P>
<P>
"There is a tendency among its journalists to demonize all
Likud politicians and supporters, and to glorify all those on the
Labor side," she said.
</P>
<P>
Then she went on to attack the radio reporters for exhorting
Arab voters to vote to save Labor's Prime Minister Shimon Peres on
the election day.
</P>
<P>
Likud leader Benjamin Netanyahu defeated Labor leader Shimon
Peres with a razor-thin lead in the election for premiership.
</P>
<P>
During the Likud celebration rally Sunday night, some Likud
supporters held posters calling for the dismissal of Channel 1
famous news anchorman Haim Yavin and Channel 2 political
correspondent Gadi Sukenik.
</P>
<P>
Razi Guterman, director of the National Federation of Israeli
Journalists, denounced Likud leaders' assault on the media and
warned that it could lead to violence against journalists.
</P>
<P>
"The hostile atmosphere they are building up will seep into
the public and cause violence," said Guterman, "It's amazing that
even before the Likud has formed a government, its first act is
intimidation and threats to settle accounts with the media."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Labor's Secretary-General Nissim Zvilli blasted
Livnat for what he called a "campaign of threats and incitement"
against the media.
</P>
<P>
Current Communications Minister Shulamit Aloni also warned that
privatizing the IBA would lead to the cancellation of cultural,
religious and educational programs, broadcasts for new immigrants
and minorities, investigations, and interviews, due to their low
ratings.
</P>
<P>
However, Likud's Prime Minister-elect Benjamin Netanyahu came
out today in defense of the media, saying "it serves a vital role
in democratic life." He said that any debate on the media's
functioning should be held in a responsible and cultured manner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
