<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 08:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No-Smoking Day Marked in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Israel today marks the No-Smoking
Day, which had been observed around the world Wednesday but
postponed here due to the national elections.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-eight percent of Israel's total population of 5.5
million smoke, and nearly one third of them puff on more than 20
cigarettes a day, a report from the Israeli Health Ministry
revealed.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that nearly one third of the male population
and one quarter of the women in Israel have the smoking habit.
</P>
<P>
Some 58 percent of this country's smokers tried to kick the
habit during the past years. More than one-tenth of the population
smoked in the past and quit, while 61 percent never smoked,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Ami Sperker, a researcher of the Health Promotion and
Prevention Medicine Department at Ben-Gurion University, has
launched a three-year study of ninth graders in Beersheba to
monitor their smoking habits.
</P>
<P>
The pupils will themselves prepare educational programs to
prevent smoking among their peers, and the researchers will see
whether this affects their smoking habits.
</P>
<P>
Sperker pointed out that according to his research, it is
clear that no-smoking teenagers have a much higher self-image
than their smoking peers.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization said earlier last week that some
3 million people around the world will die this year as a result
of smoking.
</P>
<P>
Today's observances are being organized by the Health
Ministry, the Israel Cancer Association and the Israel Forum for
the Prevention of Smoking. Special programs on smoking will be
broadcast on television during the day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
