<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mt Qomolangma Remains Pure Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The area of Mount Qomolangma remains
pure and free from litter left by mountain climbers and tourists.
</P>
<P>
At the turn of the century, the center of modern
mountain-climbing sports moved from the Alps to the Himalayas,
centering around Qomolangma. Chinese climbers opened a route on
the northern slope of Qomolangma on May 25, 1960, which was made
available to overseas climbers in 1980.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 17 years, 44 peaks in Tibet have been opened to
overseas sportsmen, and more than 10,000 people from over 30
countries and regions have explored the area.
</P>
<P>
Local authorities have taken measures to avoid problems that
might develop following a rise in mountain climbing and tourism,
according to Losang Dawa, standing vice-chairman of the Mountain
Climbers' Association of the Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The group is responsible for building permanent facilities for
the treatment of garbage in the mountainous regions, collecting
garbage in those areas twice a year, and preparing adequate
garbage bags for mountain climbers.
</P>
<P>
The association also stipulates that the visitors must protect
the wildlife and plants, and take proper precautions for any items
that might decay.
</P>
<P>
According to a 1995 report released by the Regional Bureau for
Environmental Protection, the area around the base camp on the
northern slope "has pure and clean air and may be the cleanest and
least artificially contaminated area in the world."
</P>
<P>
Losang Dawa said the Mountain Climbers' Association will
increase efforts toward environmental protection in Mount
Qomolangma by regularly removing garbage from the camp sites, and
analyzing and appraising the snow at the camp sites and mountain
peaks in cooperation with scientific institutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
