<HEADLINE> Arab Countries in Preparation for Summit on Middle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Arab countries are making
efforts to hold a summit on the prospects of the Middle East peace
process following the victory of the Likud bloc leader in Israel's
May 29 elections for premiership.
</P>
<P>
According to reports of the Saudi official news agency Saudi
Press Agency (SPA), foreign ministers of Syria, Egypt and Saudi
Arabia held talks Monday night in Saudi capital Riyadh to discuss
proposals on organizing an Arab summit in June.
</P>
<P>
Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq al-Shara and his Egyptian
counterpart Amr Moussa arrived at Riyadh just hours after talks
between Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Syrian President
Hafez al-Assad in Cairo Monday.
</P>
<P>
SPA quoted a reliable source on condition of anonymity as
saying that proposals on holding in June small or wider Arab
summits devoted to the Middle East peace process were discussed.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Mubarak and Assad held a closed-door
meeting Monday in Cairo before being joined by Shara and Moussa
and other leading members of their governments.
</P>
<P>
Assad is reported to have said that they had discussed holding
an Arab summit, adding "Egypt and Syria will pool their forces and
hope that our Arab brothers will join us."
</P>
<P>
Both the presidents had voiced pessimism for the future of the
peace process in the Middle East and urged Arabs to join their
efforts in face of a new Israeli right-wing government, media
reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
