<HEADLINE> Nigeria, Cameroon Continue Operations in Disputed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Despite a lull in hostilities on the
disputed Bakassi peninsula between Nigerian and Cameroonian
troops, the two sides are continuing massive troop deployments in
the combat zone.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here today, while Cameroon is
airlifting and shipping war material and troops from Douala, the
largest city near the Nigerian border, Nigeria is doing the same
from its border city of Calabar.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, deplomatic efforts to resolve the dispute
are intensified with Togo playing a major role behind the scenes
and the United Nations stepping in.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian head of state General Sani Abacha and the
Cameroonian President Paul Biya have agreed to meet at the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) summit to be held in Yaonde
in early July to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
Both sides have recently approved of the deployment of UN
observers mission in the disputed peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The latest round of armed clashes of the troops of both
countries caused the casulties of dozens of soldiers and
civilians and the fleeing of local citizens.
</P>
<P>
The case of the Bakassi dispute, which started in April 1994,
has already been filed before the World Court in t he Hague.
</P>
</TEXT>
