<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Cut Rice Export Tax </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has decided to cut its rice
export tariff in order to encourage rice export, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry proposed to levy a 1 percent tax on rice
that is 5 to 10 percent broken and grant free tariffs for the
export rice that is more than 15 percent broken.
</P>
<P>
Local rice exporters have complained that they are suffering
losses due to a 4 percent tax imposed previously on their export
consignments.
</P>
<P>
The cut in the export tax on low quality, 25-35 percent broken
rice is expected to help local exporters maintain their market
share.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Vietnamese government has instructed relevant
government bodies to establish an export supporting fund to help
local exporters avoid losses caused by fluctuations in the world
rice market.
</P>
<P>
Rice exporters proposed lately that the government increase the
1996 rice export quota by 500,000 tons to 2.5 million tons.
</P>
<P>
During the first quarter of this year, Vietnam exported 580,000
tons of rice. It is expected to export 600,000 tons in the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
About 65 percent of Vietnam's rice are sold in Asian markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
