<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: China's Maritime Economy Expects Promising Future (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- China's use of maritime resources
is entering a new arena with the adoption of the UN Convention on
Maritime Law.
</P>
<P>
The Standing Committee of the National People's Congress of
China decided at a meeting May 15 to abide by the UN Maritime
Convention.
</P>
<P>
An official with the National Bureau of Oceanography said that
the basic content of the UN Maritime Convention protects China's
maritime interests.
</P>
<P>
The official said that according to the convention, the sea
area under Chinese jurisdiction is about 3 million sq km. China
will develop regulations to protect its national sovereignty and
sovereignty rights from violation.
</P>
<P>
The convention establishes the understanding that the
international seabed area is the common property of mankind. It
also rules on regional exploration and development of the seabed.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, China has the right to apply for mineral zone rights
for exploration and development, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Peaceful use of maritime resources has become a marked trend
throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
In 1990, the 45th UN Assembly urged nations worldwide to list
the development and protection of maritime resources as national
development strategies; in 1994, the 49th UN Assembly named the
year 1998 as the International Maritime Year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: China's Maritime Economy Expects Promising Future (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China has a vast land territory and also boasts a wide sea
area, with a coastline stretching 18,000 kilometers. The country
has more than 6,500 offshore islands.
</P>
<P>
China's maritime economy has developed rapidly since the
implementation of reform and opening up to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that during the 1980s, the output value of the
country's maritime economy increased at an annual rate of 17
percent, while in the 1990s, the rate has exceeded 20 percent. In
1995 alone, China's output of maritime economy reached 180 billion
yuan, and the figure is expected to reach 300 billion yuan by the
year 2000, accounting for over 5 percent of the gross domestic
product.
</P>
<P>
The Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000) for National Economic and
Social Development and the Long-Range Goal for the Year 2010 also
placed great importance on developing maritime industries,
investigating and protecting maritime resources.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, China has investigated coastline and polder
resources, offshore islands, and oceanic multi-metal consumption.
</P>
<P>
The country now has formed systems to monitor maritime
environment and forecast maritime disasters, as well as a service
to provide maritime information.
</P>
<P>
Currently, aquatic farming occupies a leading position in the
country's maritime economy. Its output value was 84.3 billion yuan
in 1984 -- 60 percent of the total output value of aquatic
farming.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
