<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CAS Determines Targets for Future Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Academy of Sciences
(CAS) has set major targets for future development during China's
Ninth Five-Year Plan Period (1996-2000).
</P>
<P>
Zhou Guangzhao, President of the Chinese Academy of Sciences,
said Monday that the highlighted areas include basic science
research, research on natural resources, environment and ecology,
developing methods to aid in the promotion of the national
economy, and developing new, high-tech industries.
</P>
<P>
In his speech at the opening session of the Eighth Academicians
Conference of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, Zhou said his
academy will play an active role throughout the various
divisions. His academy is to advise and consult with leaders about
economic construction, social development and development of
science and technology.
</P>
<P>
He added that his academy also will focus on problems in
connection with the national economic development and will
encourage technical innovation in the fields of industry and
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Efforts will be made to promote the country's ecological
network and to offer scientific basis for sustainable social
development, he said.
</P>
<P>
To cater to the market-oriented economy, the Chinese Academy of
Sciences will help develop a number of high-tech ventures in areas
of information, materials, biological technology and medicine.
</P>
<P>
in the next five years, Zhou said, the academy is expected to
train more than 10,000 post-graduates, doctors and post-doctorates
for the society.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: China's Maritime Economy Expects Promising Future (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In recent years, with the rapid development of maritime
farming, development of high-value sea products was warmly
welcomed by coastal counties and cities which reaped noticeable
economic returns. Both onshore and offshore fishing have steadily
advanced.
</P>
<P>
China first tapped into maritime petroleum and natural gas in
the early 1980s, and the output of crude oil reached 8.41 million
tons in 1995. This year, the output of oil is expected to be 13
million tons, and gas output should amount to 3 billion cubic
meters.
</P>
<P>
Maritime tourism, a new sector of the country's maritime
economy, produced 26 billion yuan in output value in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The country has more than 1,500 scenic spots, including coastal
beaches and offshore islands, though a fourth of them have been
opened to tourists. It is predicted that maritime tourism will
play an important role in China's maritime economic boom.
</P>
<P>
Such development also means progress for the maritime
transportation and salt industries, and it should accelerate
direct use of sea water, and maritime medicines and food
processing industries.
</P>
<P>
At present, provinces of Shandong, Guangdong, Liaoning, Fujian,
Zhejiang, Hainan and Jiangsu all have established plans to explore
maritime development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
