<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Nigerian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Nigerian newspapers today.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian:
</P>
<P>
-- After over three years of suspension of its operations
in the disputed Ogoniland, Nigeria, Shell petroleum company
has started to come back with its new exploration of the oil
reserves. Shell withdrew from the area in South Nigeria in 1993
following clashes with the local Ogoni people who demanded a
lion's share of the oil revenues.
</P>
<P>
Third Eye:
</P>
<P>
-- Nigeria accused the Cameroonian authority of refusing to
withdraw its troops from the border areas despite a recent ruling
by the World Court in the Hague. Cameroonian forces are still
holding six border villages which the Nigerian government said
should belong to Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The Punch:
</P>
<P>
-- At least 7,000 applications from Nigerian asylum seekers
are now before the British Home Office for consideration. A
spokesman of the office said on Monday that his government has
not carried out an anti-Nigerian policy, but would reject the
demands made by the asylum seekers.
</P>
<P>
Daily Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The Nigerian government on Monday ruled out sabotage in the
latest explosions in its only armament factory, saying that its
was caused by internal combustion in the stores.
</P>
<P>
Daily Champion:
</P>
<P>
-- Ten out of the 40 condemned armed robbers who had escaped
prison in nigeria last weekend were arrested again by the police.
</P>
