<HEADLINE> Russian Prime Minister Meets Zhirinovsky </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Russian prime minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin today met with Vladimir Zhirinovsky, leader of the
Liberal Democratic Party, in the prime minister's office and the
two discussed the present domestic social and political situation.
</P>
<P>
A press secretary for the prime minister was quoted as saying
that today's meeting is one between the prime minister and a
presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
Another development is that Russian Communist leader Gennady
Zyuganov, President Boris Yeltsin's top rival, today also met with
Zhirinovsky, who has been running hard for presidency. Zyuganov
appealed to nationalists to help defeat Yeltsin in the elections
on June 16.
</P>
<P>
An opinion poll for Moscow NTV Television showed Sunday that
Yeltsin has widened his lead over Zyuganov by three percent from
last week, while Zhirinovsky trailed far behind the two of them.
</P>
<P>
Zyuganov and Zhirinovsky agreed at the meeting that the
first-ever presidential election in Russia should proceed
peacefully, the Interfax news agency quoted Zhirinovsky's
spokesman Viktor Filatov as saying.
</P>
<P>
"A common viewpoint was worked out at the meeting, that the
elections must definitely take place, and must go ahead against a
peaceful and calm background guaranteed by the current
authorities," said Filatov.
</P>
<P>
"The main thing is that there is mutual understanding, there
are points of convergence," he added.
</P>
<P>
Filatov denied that the two rivals of Yeltsin had discussed
details of any possible power shareout after the election less
than two weeks away.
</P>
<P>
Support for Yeltsin rose to 35 percent while Zyuganov trailed
with 24 percent and Zhirinovsky only five percent of the vote,
according to the latest NTV Television poll.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin was at 27.7 percent in mid-May and Zyuganov at 19.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
Eighteen percent of the Russian electorate were still
undecided.
</P>
<P>
No candidate is expected to win the June 16 elections outright
and the top two would therefore face each other in a second round
runoff poll on July 7. 
</P>
</TEXT>
