<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Launches Massive Oilsands Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien today launched massive multi-billion-dollar oilsands
projects in the western province of Albert.
</P>
<P>
More than 4.1 billion U.S. dollars of investment in the
oilsands projects was announced today at the northern Albertan
city of Fort McMurray, the Canadian Broadcasting Corporation (CBC)
Television reported tonight.
</P>
<P>
This investment will create some 10,000 new jobs for Canadians
in the next few years, the CBC said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, executives from 18 Canadian oil companies also
committed themselves to as much as 18.5 billion dollars of
investment over a 25-year period by signing the "Declaration of
Opportunity" to develop the Albert oilsands.
</P>
<P>
The Albert oilsands contain as much oil as Saudi Arabia. The
total oil reserve there is estimated to be 1.7 trillion barrels,
and the amount of oil recoverable with current technology to be at
300 billion barrels, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The only problem with oilsands is that it is mixed with sands,
and it has taken 30 years of research to profitably get the oil
out.
</P>
<P>
As conventional oil sources dry out, the oilsands are emerging
as the major new supplier of Canadian oil.
</P>
<P>
Federal and provincial changes in royalty and tax structures
are the major forces behind this massive private investment, the
CBC said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
