<HEADLINE> News Analysis: France Succeeds in NATO Reform Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- NATO's agreement today to set up a
European component of the U.S.-dominated military alliance is
being hailed here as a success for France in its fight for a role
for itself, and for greater power for Europe, within the
organization.
</P>
<P>
In historic changes to European defense structure, the European
wing of NATO will be given more independence and be able to launch
its own peacekeeping or relief missions using borrowed
U.S. military hardware such as intelligence, communications and
airlift equipment.
</P>
<P>
The plan will also give European nations more flexibility and
resources to deal with regional crises in Europe by allowing the
Western European Union, the 10-nation European defense
organization, to run operations using American military assets but
without involving U.S. ground forces.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.S. will still have power to veto missions and
use of its hardware through NATO's policy-making body, the North
Atlantic Council, which will have to authorize any operation.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher said the NATO
agreement, widely seen as a major step towards the building of a
European defense pillar, will shift more responsibility onto
Europe and is in the interests of European countries, notably
France.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Herve de Charette hailed the agreement
as a great success, saying it is the first time in the the history
of the 47-year-old alliance that Europe's role has been made clear.
</P>
<P>
"For the first time in alliance history, Europe will really be
able to express its personality," he said.
</P>
<P>
De Charette added that France was now ready to play a full role
in a revamped NATO.
</P>
<P>
France has been bargaining its return to NATO's integrated
military command structure after 30 years of boycott in exchange
for NATO reform toward a more European military wing.
</P>
<P>
As part of its bid and move closer to the trans-Atlantic
alliance, France decided last year that its defense minister and
armed forces chief of staff could attend NATO meetings.
</P>
<P>
France's recent rapprochement with NATO, including its active
participation in NATO's Peace Implementation Force (IFOR) in
Bosnia, helped pave the way for this new agreement to set up a
European combined joint task force (CJTF).
</P>
<P>
The principle of the CJTF was first proposed in January 1994 by
the U.S. at the NATO summit in Brussels, aimed at shifting more of
the alliance's responsibilities to Europe and allowing more
flexibility in military operations.
</P>
<P>
But the plan stalled over differences between Washington and
Paris over the role and influence of the U.S. over NATO staff,
equipment and headquarters. The ensuing wrangle between the
U.S. and Europe, led by France, was eased by the French
rapprochement.
</P>
<P>
But analysts say France still has a long way to go to create a
clear European identity as the U.S. is reluctant to relinquish its
direct control over NATO's military firepower.
</P>
<P>
Under this new agreement, the U.S. still preserves the ultimate
power to use U.S. forces, and the power to supervise and veto any
NATO operations.
</P>
<P>
And although the Europeans could act on their own, a
U.S. official said he expected those operations would be "smaller
scale missions" and "very few and far between".
</P>
<P>
A U.S. representative to the Berlin meeting also said Europe
does not have the capacity to handle regional crises without the
United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
