<HEADLINE> Accidents Cost Canada Seven Billion Dollars Yearly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Workplaces accidents have cost
Canada a total of 7.3 billion U.S. dollars in direct and indirect
losses every year.
</P>
<P>
Two Canadians are killed each day in a workplace accident, and
one out of every 15 Canadian workers can expect to be injured on
the job.
</P>
<P>
"These personal and economic costs can only be eliminated
through effective accidents prevention," Canadian Labor Minister
Alfonso Gagliano said, adding that prevention requires constant
awareness and active participation of employers and workers
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
The minister made these remarks at a press conference here in
opening Canadian Occupational Safety and Health (COSH) Week, which
starts today.
</P>
<P>
"Governments (at all levels) must continue to improve
legislation on occupational safety and health, and interested
organizations must continue working to strengthen Canadian
awareness of the need for accident prevention measures," Gagliano
said.
</P>
<P>
However, the key to eliminating all accidents is the constant
personal commitment of every employer and worker, the minister
added.
</P>
<P>
The COSH week, the tenth this year, is designed to remind all
Canadians that accidents prevention in the workplaces is
everyone's business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
