<HEADLINE> South Korean President Names National Assembly Speaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 4 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim Young-sam
nominated Kim Soo-han of the ruling New Korea Party (NKP) as
National Assembly speaker today.
</P>
<P>
President Kim, who heads the ruling party, also named Oh
Se-eung vice National Assembly speaker, NKP spokesman Kim Chul
announced here.
</P>
<P>
The house speaker-nominee Kim, 68, has been elected to the
National Assembly six times and had served as spokesman and senior
member of opposition parties before joining the ruling party in
1990. He was elected a parliament lawmaker on the ruling party's
national representation ticket in the general elections last April.
</P>
<P>
Vice speaker-nominee Oh, 63, is a seven-term legislator and
formerly served as state minister for political affairs and
Chairman of the National Assembly Culture-Information committee.
</P>
<P>
The ruling NKP plans to convene a special parliamentary session
tomorrow to approve the nomination of speaker and vice speaker of
the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
However, the main opposition National Congress for New Politics
(NCNP) headed by Kim Dae-jung and the conservative opposition
United Liberal Democrats (ULD) led by Kim Jong-pil are still
threatening to boycott the house session in protest of the
government and the ruling party's recruitment of opposition and
independent lawmakers-elect to secure a majority in the National
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
In the 15th South Korean National Assembly elections held on
April 11, the ruling NKP won 139 seats, 11 short of a simple
majority in the 299-seat parliament.
</P>
<P>
But, the NKP later lured into its fold 12 lawmakers-elect,
mostly independents, to secure 151 seats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
