<HEADLINE> Indian Government Hints at Market-Friendly Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Indian Finance Minister P.
Chidambaram has indicated that the new government will continue
economic reforms launched by the last Congress government five
years ago despite differences over several issues within the
ruling coalition.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued on Monday, Chidambaram said his policies
would include fiscal prudence and austerity, the continuation of
tax reforms, attracting both foreign and domestic capital,
achieving a higher level of investment and channeling it into the
infrastructure industry, according to local press reports today.
</P>
<P>
Chidambaram said he would pursue the reform and restructuring
of the public sector and the reform and opening up of the
agricultural sector, boost export, improve the efficiency of
public services and utilities, and target subsidies at the needy
and poor.
</P>
<P>
He admitted there were differences among the United Front which
formed the new government on June 1, and expressed the hope that
the front was committed to reconciling the differences and
enlarging the areas of consensus.
</P>
<P>
The new finance minister, who issued the statement after
meeting senior officials of his ministry on his first day in
office, declined to further specify the policies because the
common minimum program of the government had not yet been
formalized.  
</P>
