<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First No-Smoking Street Emerges in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 4 (Xinhua) -- China's first no-smoking street
has emerged in the country's largest city, with no-smoking signs
posted at both ends of the street.
</P>
<P>
The 400-meter-long Pingliang Road in the northeast part of the city
has erected two steel boards proclaiming the ban against smoking
on the street.
</P>
<P>
This move is part of a growing anti-smoking campaign in the city.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from 62 shops, hospitals and schools along the
street have signed no-smoking agreements with the community
office, sources said.
</P>
<P>
Local police and community supervisors will oversee the new
restrictions. More streets are intended to join in the
anti-smoking drive.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai first encouraged people to stop smoking in 1987 and
since December 1, 1994, smoking has been banned in all public
places, including theaters, restaurants and conference halls whose
area exceeds 200 square meters.
</P>
<P>
Beijing officially banned smoking in public places as of May 15.
</P>
</TEXT>
