<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Rebel's Ammunition Found in South India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Indian authorities have
recovered 17,000 rounds of ammunition in a Sri Lankan Tamil
rebel's hideout on the southern Indian coast, according to reports
reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The ammunition was mainly 7.62 round for T-56 rifles and
Russian AK 47s.
</P>
<P>
According to defense sources, the Indian security authorities
are remaining on alert to combat Tamil rebels using Southern India
as a transit point for armaments coming to Sri Lanka, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
India banned the rebels of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam
(LTTE) on May 4, 1992 after they assassinated former Indian Prime
Minister Rajiv Gandhi.
</P>
<P>
They have also sought the extradition of LTTE's head Velupillai
 Prabhakaran, intelligence chief Pottu Amman and head of the
women's brigade Akila.
</P>
<P>
Akila, who had trained the suicide bomber who killed Rajiv
Gandhi, was reported to have been killed in the Sri Lankan
government's major military operation in Jaffna Peninsula last
November.
</P>
<P>
According to local press reports, the LTTE fighting for a
separate Tamil state in the north and east of Sri Lanka is facing
a serious shortage of ammunition.  
</P>
