<HEADLINE> Mexico Slaps Anti-Dumping Tariff on Russian Steel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Mexican government is to
maintain its year-old anti-dumping tariff on rolled steel imported
from Russia.
</P>
<P>
The 29.3 percent tariff was imposed in June last year, after
the government found Russian rolled steel was entering Mexico at
subsidized prices, boosting sales and its share of the Mexican
market to the detriment of domestic steel producers.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce and Industrial Promotion Ministry has now ratified
the measure to comply with the "external trade and industrial
policy program" on unfair international trade practices, according
to an official gazette here today.
</P>
<P>
Rolled steel is used to make boilers, pressure cookers, gas
cylinders, automobile tire rims, ships and water and oil pipes.
</P>
</TEXT>
