<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Petroleum Consumption Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Thailand consumed 869,110 barrels
of petroleum per day on average in the first four months of this
year, up 9.1 percent more than that in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Figures released Monday by the Petroleum Authority of Thailand
(PTT) showed continued high growth in demand fueled by rapid
domestic economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
Demand for refined oil products jumped 10.6 percent in the
period to 724,260 barrels per day, while use of indigenous natural
gas as fuel rose by 2.2 percent to 144,850 barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
Rising demand boosted the country's procurement of petroleum by
10.9 percent to an average of 983,410 barrels per day, including
731,510 barrels from overseas sources (up 14.6 percent) and
251,900 barrels from indigenous oil and gas fields (up 1.3
percent).
</P>
<P>
Oil imports accounted for 74.4 percent of the total supply of
petroleum in the country in the January-April period.
</P>
<P>
Crude oil imports jumped 18.5 percent to 529,940 barrels per
day while finished oil product imports rose 5.4 percent to 201,570
barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
Production of indigenous natural gas rose 2.3 percent to
197,800 barrels per day, crude oil output dropped 2.8 percent to
24,000 barrels per day while condensate production remained flat
at 30,100 barrels per day.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Leader to Return to Nepal's Ruling Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 4 (Xinhua) -- A former leader of the Nepali
Congress (NC), the country's main ruling party, will rejoin the
party's leadership after nearly two years' absence.
</P>
<P>
NC General Secretary Taranath Ranabhat disclosed Monday in
Pokhara of Western Nepal that Ganesh Man Singh, co-founder of the
NC party, had agreed to join the party again, reports reaching
here today said.
</P>
<P>
The NC leader said the newly-elected NC President, Girija
Prasad Koirala, resolved to bring the party to its former state of
unity and to strength, referring to the NC's majority control in
the parliament before the 1994 mid-term election.
</P>
<P>
Singh, who founded the NC with two others 49 years ago, quit
the party in 1994 when the then prime minister Koirala announced
to dissolve the parliament and call for the mid-term polls.
</P>
<P>
Koirala resorted to the mid-term election due to the
intra-party differences over his government policy program which
was rejected by the Lower House, where his NC party held a
majority.
</P>
<P>
Dissidents in the NC requested him to resign from the post of
prime minister after the defeat of his program.
</P>
<P>
However, the NC lost its majority in the November 1994 mid-term
election and became the second largest party in the parliament
after the Communist Party of Nepal (UML), which later led a
nine-month-long minority government.
</P>
<P>
The present coalition government was formed last September by
the NC and two small parties after they jointly toppled the UML
government through a no-confidence vote in the House.
</P>
<P>
Ganesh Man Singh started his political career in 1940 when
Nepal was under the rule of the Rana regime.
</P>
<P>
He was elected NC's life-long supreme leader in 1982 after the
death of the renowned NC leader B.P. Koirala and led the 1990
people's movement which eventually overthrew the 30-year-long
partyless panchayat system in Nepal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
