<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Warns Germany of Wide Budget Gap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) today
urged Germany to lower its budget deficit to meet conditions for
its switch to an EU-wide single currency system.
</P>
<P>
EU finance ministers placed Germany on a list of nations whose
budget deficit has gone beyond 3 percent of gross domestic product
(GDP), according to reports reaching here from Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
Bringing deficit down to 3 percent of GDP is the target for
countries aiming to adopt Europe's single currency, known as "the
euro," when it is launched on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Germany is the EU's biggest economy and the main driving force
for establishing the monetary union. But its deficit rose to 3.5
percent last year, when it experienced a sharp economic slowdown.
</P>
<P>
Of the 15 EU member countries, only the three smallest ones --
Ireland, Luxembourg and Denmark -- are not on the deficit warning
list.
</P>
<P>
Besides the deficit list, EU ministers meeting in Luxembourg
went on making preparations for the single currency.
</P>
<P>
They drafted plans proposed by Germany to fine those nations
that threaten the financial stability of the currency union by
raising high deficits after they adopt the euro.
</P>
<P>
Despite its own problem meeting the condition, Germany held
that the EU stick to all the criteria for joining the currency
union, including low inflation and public debt, and stable
exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
In addition, EU ministers have outlined plans to limit exchange
rate fluctuation between the euro and currencies of those
countries that stay outside the single currency system after
1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smaller Australian Wheat Crop Expected Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Australian wheat crop is
expected to be smaller in 1996-97 than in this year.
</P>
<P>
Wheat harvests are expected to fall slightly to 16.1 million
tons in the coming year from 16.6 million tons in 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
The current sowing was delayed by persistent dry weather in
southern and western Australia, though positive prospect of wheat
prices was expected to boost planting areas, the Australian Bureau
of Agricultural and Resources Economics (ABARE) announced today.
</P>
<P>
In its first forecast of next year's harvests, ABARE expects
that wheat planting areas will increase 10 percent over the last
season to 10.9 million hectares.
</P>
<P>
"On the basis of current planting intentions being realized and
assuming normal rainfall through to harvest, total wheat
production in Australia in 1996-97 is forecast to be 16.1 million
tons," ABARE announced.
</P>
<P>
ABARE Acting Director Stephen Beare said that depressed prices
for wool and beef had prompted farmers to shift to grain
production.
</P>
<P>
He said that total winter grain planting areas were expected to
increase five percent over the last season to 17.6 million
hectares.
</P>
<P>
Barley planting is expected to rise to 3.3 million hectares,
with production at 5.3 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Good rains in the northeastern part of the country secure ideal
conditions for local winter crops, while south and west waited for
crucial rainfall in the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
"Rain in the next two weeks will be critical if the full
(Western Australia) area potential is to be realized," the
forecast said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
