<HEADLINE> WTO Rules Brighten Thai Exports to New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Thai exporters should have good
opportunities in New Zealand once the government cuts tariffs on
more than 800 items in compliance with the World Trade
Organization (WTO) requirements.
</P>
<P>
According to a report from the Business Economics Department of
the Thai government, the WTO liberalization requirements will
prompt New Zealand to lower barriers on 843 items of imports.
</P>
<P>
The products are potential Thai exports to New Zealand,
generating an export value of 1.88 billion baht (75 million US
dollars) from Thailand a year.
</P>
<P>
The items include frozen shrimp, teleprinters, synthetic
fibers, chemicals and machinery parts.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, New Zealand will stop collecting tariffs on 19 items
of Thai exports, with a combined export value of 90 million baht
(3.6 million US dollars). The products in this group include color
television, wood pulp, tractors, tissue and glass lenses.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand will also reduce tariffs on tomatoes, shoes, milk,
cream, diamonds, electric lamps and women's underwear.  
</P>
</TEXT>
