<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Education Ministry to Lighten Students' Bags </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Education Ministry is
introducing measures to ease students' burden as concern about
students' health rose in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to a decision made by the ministry Monday, the total
weight of bags (including books) for kindergartners will be one
kilogram at most, for Grade 1-6 pupils not over two kilograms, and
for Grade 7-12 students not more than three kilograms.
</P>
<P>
All schools under the Office of the National Primary Education
Commission, the Department of General Education, and the Office of
the Private Education Commission are required to follow the
instruction.
</P>
<P>
Worried about the negative effect of carrying heavy school bags
on the growth system and bone structures of children, the ministry
suggested that students carry only several necessary items to
school in their bags everyday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also required that new school buildings to be
constructed supply lockers for students to keep their belongings
to be used in classes, so they do not have to carry heavy bags
back and forth between home and school.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ministry required schools to set aside at least
one hour a day for Grade 1-6 students to do homework at school.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany's GDP Drops for Second Quarter in Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Germany's gross domestic product (GDP)
dropped slightly again in the first quarter this year, making it
qualified for the definition of a recession.
</P>
<P>
The 0.2 to 0.5 percent drop, to be announced by the Federal
Statistics Office in Wiesbaden on Wednesday, followed a 0.5
percent drop in the last quarter of 1995.
</P>
<P>
Two successive quarters of GDP decline constitutes an economic
recession from the statistical viewpoint, although the government
has refused to admit the current one.
</P>
<P>
The government's denials are based on assurances that economic
growth is going to resume. Economics Minister Guenter Rexrodt
said that he expects sustained GDP growth of 2 to 2.5 percent for
the second half of this year.
</P>
<P>
The government projects an annual growth of 0.75 percent this
year although experts predict the growth will be only 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the October-March recession mainly resulted
from a sudden fall in production and investments in the
construction industry under the severe winter weather conditions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
