<HEADLINE> Jakarta Seeks 5 Billion US Dollars in CGI Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia is seeking at least 5
billion US dollars in financial assistance from the World
Bank-chaired Consultative Group for Indonesia (CGI) this year,
local press quoting a senior official as saying today.
</P>
<P>
Minister for National Development Planning Ginandjar
Kartasasmita said Monday in Surabaya, the second largest city in
the country, that the government requested Japan in particular not
to reduce its commitment during the donor group's meeting in Paris
on June 18-20.
</P>
<P>
He said Indonesia asked Japan to increase its loan commitment
in yen so that the value of the Japanese loan would not decline in
terms of the dollar.
</P>
<P>
The US dollar has appreciated by about 20 percent against the
Japanese yen to approximately 105 yen to the dollar from 87 yen in
June last year.
</P>
<P>
"The appreciation of the US dollar against the yen will be one
of the important subjects to be raised in the coming CGI meeting,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank said recently that it would recommend to the CGI
that it provide at least the same amount as last year at their
coming meeting.
</P>
<P>
CGI creditors provided 5.36 billion US dollars in financial aid
to Indonesia last year.
</P>
<P>
Japan, the single largest creditor, pledged 187.6 billion yen
(2.14 billion US dollars at the rate of 87.5 yen per dollar) last
year.
</P>
<P>
The CGI, set up in 1992 to replace the inter-governmental group
on Indonesia, groups Australia, Austria, Belgium, Canada, Denmark,
Finland, France, Britain, Germany, Italy, Japan, New Zealand,
Norway, Spain, Sweden, Switzerland, South Korea, the Kuwait Fund
for Arab Economic Development, the Saudi Fund for Development
Bank, the Islamic Development Bank and the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
