<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bankruptcy Cases on Rise in Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Personal and business bankruptcy cases
in Germany amounted to 7,555 in the first quarter of this year in
what seemed to be a ongoing economic downturn trend.
</P>
<P>
The total number of bankruptcies, according to a Federal
Statistics Office report from Wiesbaden today, represented an 8.8
percent rise over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
As a result, creditor claims totaled 11 billion German marks,
or 7.22 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Some 29,000 businesses became insolvent in 1995, and about
32,000 are expected to follow in 1996, making it the 5th year in a
row that bankruptcy cases have been on the rise.
</P>
<P>
The hardest hit has been eastern Germany, where 1,746
bankruptcies were reported in the first three months of the year,
a 38 percent increase over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
In the west, meanwhile, bankruptcy cases rose 6.6 percent to a
total of 4,344 cases.
</P>
<P>
Germany's economy is estimated to have contracted for the
second straight quarter in the first three months of 1996, with
severe winter weather depressing construction, which had been a
key part of the eastern German growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
