<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France to Cut Tax: Juppe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Alain Juppe
today announced that his government will adopt a five-year tax
cutting plan, in a bid to ease tax pressure on companies and
individuals.
</P>
<P>
Juppe told a press conference that the plan to be put into
effect at the start of 1997 will bring changes to the present
system of income brackets and eliminate disincentives to
investment.
</P>
<P>
But the prime minister did not give full details, saying that
the project will be presented to the National Assembly and be
unveiled alongside the 1997 budget in September.
</P>
<P>
Since assuming office one year ago, Juppe's government, which
had pledged in the election campaign to ease tax pressure, has
raised taxes on several occasions in an effort to reduce the
social security deficit and narrow a growing budget gap.
</P>
<P>
The government's actions have triggered public discontent and
protest, which had led to three-week-long nation-wide strikes in
last December.
</P>
<P>
The tax cutting plan, aiming to spur consumption and at the
same time reduce the budget deficit, will lower "the overall scale
of income tax" over the next five years, said Juppe.
</P>
<P>
In other measures, he said, professional taxes will be reformed
with an aim to reduce the impact on new investors, and the special
levies imposed since the start of this year in a bid to cut
France's massive deficits will be phased out.
</P>
<P>
But the socialist opposition said the pledge to cut taxes is
intended to help the government win the 1998 legislative elections
and accused it of favoring those in the higher income brackets.
</P>
<P>
France is one of the countries having the highest tax rates in
the world, with the annual tax revenues in the government's 1996
budget totaling 1,400 billion francs (about 280 billion U.S.
dollars), an increase of 7.6 percent from the 1,300 billion francs
(260 billion dollars) in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's Largest Power Plant at Full Capacity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's Itaipu
hydroelectric power plant, the largest in the world, today began
operating in full swing to meet the increasing demand in the south
American country, general manager Euclides Scalco said today.
</P>
<P>
Itaipu will generate 80 million gigawatts/hour of electricity
in 1996, compared with last year's 77 million.
</P>
<P>
Seventeen of the eighteen 700-MW turbine generators are
currently operating at the Itaipu power station, with one
generator under maintenance.
</P>
<P>
The installment of another 700-MW turbine is under study as
demand had increased by 3 percent in the first four months of
1996, compared with the corresponding period of 1995, and by 8.6
percent last year over the same period of 1994.
</P>
<P>
Electricity consumption is expected to rise by an average of
5.6 percent annually in the next few years until 2015. 
</P>
</TEXT>
