<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dengue Fever Toll Increases to 117 in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- An outbreak of dengue fever, a
cholera-like disease, in Indonesia's 27 provinces has killed 117
people and hospitalized more than 5,000 others over the past five
months, local press reported today quoting a senior health
official.
</P>
<P>
Director General of Communicable Disease Control and
Environmental Health Hadi M. Abednego said here that East Java
recorded the highest rate, with 2,484 hospitalized and 57 deaths.
Jakarta came second with 1,880 hospitalized and 28 deaths,
followed by West Java with 523 hospitalized and 11 deaths.
</P>
<P>
Dengue fever, an acute tropical disease transmitted by
mosquitoes, usually hits densely-populated areas and affects
children who spend most of their time outdoors. The disease leaves
its victims with fever, sash and severe pains in the joints and
back.
</P>
<P>
The cholera-like disease, known locally as "muntaber", causes
vomiting and diarrhea.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0277 </DOCNO>
