<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albania's Ruling Democrats Show Strong in Runoffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, May 3 (Xinhua) -- Albania's ruling Democratic party
further widened its parliamentary majority today in the second
round of the general election, taking six out of nine seats
undecided after last week's first round.
</P>
<P>
But the six main opposition parties refused to take part in the
runoffs, continuing their boycott launched midway through the
first round when they accused the governing Democrats of vote
rigging.
</P>
<P>
The conservative Democrats, who won 95 of the 115 single-member
constituencies in the first round of voting on April 26, now
control 10l of the 140 seats in the one-chamber parliament, the
People's Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Before the election, they held 92 seats against 38 for the main
Socialist opposition party.
</P>
<P>
Final results of the runoffs issued tonight by the Central
Electoral Commission gave the Republican Party two seats and the
Balli Kombetax Party one seat. The losers were the Union of Human
Rights, set up by ethnic Greeks in southern Albania, and two other
lesser right-wing groupings.
</P>
<P>
Voter turnout was 59.2 percent, much lower than the 89 percent
in the first round.
</P>
<P>
The commission, a state body in charge of organizing and
overseeing the election, said fresh voting would be held soon in
the remaining four constituencies where "serious irregularities"
had been observed.
</P>
<P>
Under the election law, 115 of the 140 parliamentary seats are
contested in single-member constituencies and the remaining 25 are
allocated to the 12 parties which win the most votes in the first
round by proportional representation.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the Socialist Party and five other opposition groups
have refused to accept the election results and demanded another
vote. They have demanded that polling be repeated in at least 80
of the 115 constituencies.
</P>
<P>
More than 70 opposition candidates have been on hunger strike
in the capital city since Saturday in an attempt to force a fresh
poll.
</P>
<P>
Tension has gripped the country since April 27 when riot police
broke up a mass opposition rally staged in central Tirana in
protest at alleged ballot rigging. But the opposition vowed not
to bow to government intimidation and would continue to call
peaceful protests across the country.
</P>
<P>
The European Union (EU) and the Organization for the Security
and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) have rapped the Albanian
government for "a lot of irregularities" observed by their
monitors overseeing the first round of balloting.
</P>
<P>
Italy, current holder of the EU rotating presidency, has called
on Albania to hold a partial re-run of the election. But the
Central Electoral Commission, which the opposition and foreign
observers said was appointed by the government, only admitted
there were some irregularities and have rejected the demand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
