<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 2 Million Ecuadoran Children Live in Poverty: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Nearly half the children in Ecuador,
more than 2.3 million, live in poverty, making it difficult for
them to go to school and forcing many into work, often without any
protection or social security benefits, a new report says.
</P>
<P>
There are an estimated 500,000 child laborers in the Latin
American country, a quarter of whom work without any social
security benefits, a document released today by the country's
Child Labor Program (PMT) says.
</P>
<P>
Of the 5 million under 18 living in Ecuador, some 4 million
live without the support of any social system to protect their
lives and development.
</P>
<P>
The report also found that 30 percent of children have suffered
some kind of sexual abuse and that 50 percent of parents and 54
percent of teachers abuse children in some way.
</P>
<P>
Of those abused, 87 percent are depressed but more than a third
believe they deserve their maltreatment.
</P>
<P>
Ecuadoran minors under 18 account for about 45 percent of the
country's 11 million population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
