<HEADLINE> Namibian Fredericks Wins 100m Sprint in France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Namibian Frankie Fredericks showed
his top form to take the men's 100 meters in a winning timing of
9.95 seconds at the International Athletics Meets in Saint-Denis,
France on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Olympic runner-up at both 100 and 200 meters, levelled his
personal best set in 1991, beating Nigerian Olapade Adeniken to
second in 10.17 and American Terry Bowen third in 10.19.
</P>
<P>
However, Fredericks who recently trained with Briton Linford
Christie, said he had not decided to compete in either 100m or
200m in the coming Olympics.
</P>
<P>
His winning score was one of the best in the season.
</P>
<P>
Trinidad's Ato Boldon clocked 9.93 in April and ran the world
best of 9.92 in Eugene on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Last month, American Dennis Mitchell also clocked 9.93 in
Atlanta where Carl Lewis finished second in 9.94.
</P>
<P>
Also in Saint-Denis, Michael Johnson, bidder for the doubles in
the 200m and 400m in the coming Olympic Games, won the 200 meters
in 20.23 seconds, his only race in Europe prior to the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Compatriot Ramon Clay finished a distant second in 20.62 and
Cuban Ivan Garcia third in 20.72.
</P>
<P>
Algerian world champion Noureddine Morceli won the 1,500 meters
in 3:32.47, a far cry from his own world record of 3:27.37 set in
Nice last year.
</P>
<P>
In the women's 200 meters, French Marie Jose Perec, world
champion in 400 meters, beat her rivals en route to her victory
with the season's best of 22.30 seconds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
