<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnian Serbs Urge Muslim-Croat Federation to Free POWs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Bosnian Serbs today appealed to
the Bosnian Muslim-Croat Federation to release 1,300 prisoners of
war and 1,000 civilians who the Serbs claimed were still held
captive by the Muslims and Croats.
</P>
<P>
Momir Talic, commander of the Bosnian Serb military forces
around Banjaluka, made the appeal while meeting with Michael
Jackson, commander of the southwestern district of the NATO-led
multinational peacekeeping force, and Pierre Kraehenbuhl, chief of
the International Red Cross delegation to Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The Bosnian Serbs have handed over to Jackson and Kraehenbuhl a
list of the 2,300 POWs and civilians, and Talic urged the two men
to help with the release of the POWs and civilians.
</P>
<P>
The Dayton peace accord, signed last December, stipulates that
all parties to the three-and-a-half-year Bosnian war should set
free all prisoners of war and civilians by January this year.
</P>
<P>
But the Muslim-Croat Federation and Bosnian Serbs are believed
to be still holding Serb POWs and civilians.
</P>
<P>
Jackson told the press after meeting Talic that the release and
resettlement of POWs and civilians in Bosnia need more efforts
from the international community, as well as more goodwill from
all previous warring parties in the former Yugoslav region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
