<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenzhen, Hong Kong Jointly Expanding High-Tech Industry (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Manufacturers in Shenzhen in
Guangdong Province and neighboring Hong Kong have been joining
hands to expand high-tech industries.
</P>
<P>
Of 63 high-tech companies in Shenzhen, 23 are joint ventures
between Shenzhen and Hong Kong companies, according to Li Lianhe,
director of the Shenzhen City Science and Technology Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Li said that the joint high-tech ventures turned out 6.5
billion yuan worth-of goods last year and reached combined sales
of 6.2 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Flexible policies are being pursued in the Shenzhen Special
Economic Zone to encourage investors from Hong Kong, Macao and
overseas.
</P>
<P>
Li said, "I think Shenzhen and Hong Kong enjoy bright prospects
for expanding the high-tech industry because the economies of the
two places supplement each other's needs."
</P>
<P>
He said that Hong Kong's funds and Shenzhen's personnel are
being used to develop new high-tech products.
</P>
<P>
The Huayuan Company has introduced funds from Hong Kong and
employed well-trained people in Shenzhen. As a result it
manufactured computer floppy disks worth 250 million yuan in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The Science and Intelligence Linguistic Information Processing
Company has developed IQ English-Chinese translation system in
cooperation with a Hong Kong Company. Last year 1.3 million units
of the system were produced, with exports valued at 600 million HK
dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenzhen, Hong Kong Jointly Expanding High-Tech Industry (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Li Lianhe said, "High-tech companies are trying to break into
global markets with the help of Hong Kong managerial staff."
</P>
<P>
For instance, guided by the members from Hong Kong of a Board
of Directors, the Shenzhen Science and Technology Development
Company earned 1.59 billion yuan from exporting 20 million
magnetic heads last year, ranking third in the world.
</P>
<P>
Proximity to Hong Kong has been a great convenience for imports
and exports from Shenzhen, he said.
</P>
<P>
IBM, Compaq and six other internationally-known high-tech
companies have built plants in Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
The Shenzhen City government has decided to focus on expanding
seven high-tech industries over the next five years: computers,
microelectronics, integration of machinery and electronics,
telecommunications, biology engineering, new materials and laser.
</P>
<P>
Li invited more Hong Kong companies to become involved in
expanding the industries.
</P>
<P>
He said that the local government plans to take effective
measures to promote Shenzhen-Hong Kong cooperation in the
high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
The Shenzhen and Hong Kong High-Tech Industrial Development
Zone will be opened soon, he said, adding that an engineering
research center and a technology trade center will be built.
</P>
<P>
Lawyers' offices, assessment agencies, design companies and
accounting offices in Hong Kong will be encouraged to provide
intermediate services to high-tech companies in Shenzhen, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
