<HEADLINE> Peru to Export More Farm Produce This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Exports of Peruvian agricultural
produce is expected to earn 760 million U.S. dollars this year, an
increase of 17 percent over 1995, exporters have said.
</P>
<P>
Exports of traditional and non-traditional agricultural produce
in January-April this year rose to more than 105 million dollars
which represents an increase of 18 percent over the same period in
1995, said a report from the Association of Peruvian Exporters.
</P>
<P>
If this rate of growth could continue, Peru would probably be
able to export 1 billion dollars worth of goods before the year
2000, the association said.
</P>
<P>
The volume of non-traditional products is increasing
considerably and new and different products are appearing which
will enable Peru to consolidate its presence as an exporting
country.
</P>
<P>
Among the farm produce are dried vegetables, onions, garlic,
hearts of palm, cocoa and olives that have been well received in
foreign markets and for which they have been able to obtain good
prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Ratifies First BOT Power Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- China's first power project to be
constructed using the BOT (build, operate, transfer) method has
been approved by relevant government departments.
</P>
<P>
The plant will be solely funded by the International Energy
Group (IEG) of the United States, with a total investment of 1.2
billion US dollars, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Under the BOT method, a private firm is allowed to build and
operate a project for a certain period of time, after which
ownership of the project is passed to the government.
</P>
<P>
The plant, to be built in Changshu, east China's Jiangsu
province, will be built and operated by Jiangsu Power Construction
Corp with an operation period of 20 years.
</P>
<P>
The US company will bear the investment risks, while China will
be responsible for other risks. According to official sources, the
power project, with two 600,000-kilowatt generating units, will
begin operation with the first unit starting power generation in
2000.
</P>
<P>
A provincial official said the foreign investor can sell its
shares after the power project is built and can also expand its
investment project to related business areas upon approval.
</P>
<P>
As China's largest industrial province, Jiangsu produced 940.1
billion yuan in industrial output value in 1995. Though the
province has an installed power capacity of over 10 million
kilowatts, it has a serious power shortage due to rapid economic
development.
</P>
<P>
The province plans to build power plants with nine million
kilowatts in installed capacity during the Ninth Five-Year Plan
period (1996-2000). The province is seeking two billion US dollars
in foreign funds, about 25 percent of the total investment
needed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
