<HEADLINE> Olympic Torch Relay Reaches Half-Way in US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua/OANA) -- The Olympic flame reached
half-way in the United States when 77 runners carried it across
Chicago to Indiana on Monday, the 22nd of 42 host states prior to
the opening ceremony on July 19 in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
The flame was carried to Chicago by a special train from
Wisconsin after making brief stops at Waukegan, Lake Forest,
Highland Park and Evanston.
</P>
<P>
Chicago, one of a handful of cities where the torch made more
than one stop, cheered for its arrival on the 38th of the 84 days
scheduled for the relay.
</P>
<P>
The torch arrived at the Northwestern Metra Station, west of
Chicago's Loop, aboard a 19-car Union Pacific train from Milwaukee
shortly after noon.
</P>
<P>
It made the way to Grant Park behind schedule under a heavy
cloud, but the final runner was able to light the Olympic Cauldron
before any rains could fall.
</P>
<P>
A few thousand supporters gathered at the band shell to watch
the spectacle, as well as to listen to the Grant Park Symphony
Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
Olympics expert John MacAloon was instrumental in bringing the
torch to the University of Chicago Hyde Park campus, where
University President Hugo Sonnenschein helped light a cauldron in
the center of the Main Quadrangle.
</P>
<P>
From the University, the torch was carried to Gary, Indiana.
</P>
<P>
The torch will pass through over 100,000 hands along its
15,000-mile relay from Olympia, Greece, to Atlanta. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
