<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retail Price of Jewelry Liberalized on Trial Basis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, June 4 (Xinhua) -- In a move to reconsider the
pricing practices now in place, China's central bank for the first
time is allowing shops to freely set retail prices for gold
jewelry on a trial basis.
</P>
<P>
The green light has been given to jewelry shops in the Gold
Jewelry Plaza in the Shenzhen Special Economic Zone, and is
expected to extend to all the shops in the zone in three to four
months, providing the experiment proves successful. Shenzhen,
adjacent to Hong Kong, accounts for 20 percent of gold jewelry
sold by wholesale.
</P>
<P>
While producers were allowed to set the ex-factory prices
according to the design and craftsmanship of gold jewelry, the
retailers could only be allowed to sell jewelry at state-set
unified prices, which were determined by the weight of each piece,
according to Shen Ruming, a division chief of the Shenzhen Branch
of the People's Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
"This has led shops to only sell gold jewelry of simple design
and mediocre technique since their ex-factory price was lower,"
Shen told Xinhua in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
Under the new system introduced at the end of May, the jewelry
shops in the Gold Jewelry Plaza are now allowed to price their
jewelry based on a combination of three factors: the retail price
set according to the ex-factory price, the craftsmanship fee, and
a five percent consumer tax.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
