<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rica Ink Inter-American Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican Foreign Minister
Fernando Naranjo signed here today the inter-American convention
concerning the forced disappearance of persons and for the
compliance of criminal sentences abroad.
</P>
<P>
The signing ceremony was held here on the eve of the
inauguration of the 26th period of session of the General Assembly
of the Organization of American States (OAS).
</P>
<P>
After the ceremony, Naranjo said that even though his country
has not had any cases of forced disappearance of persons, "it has
always repudiated, vehemently, that crime against humanity which
in the painful past has lacerated the conscience of several
countries in this hemisphere."
</P>
<P>
The document was signed in the 1994 General Assembly of the OAS
at the end of a lengthy process that began in 1987, when the
Inter-American Commission on Human Rights proposed that a
convention be adopted in this regard.
</P>
<P>
The Inter-American Convention for the Compliance of Criminal
Sentences Abroad, adopted in the 1993 general assembly of the OAS,
was designed to encourage and promote cooperation among its 35
member states to ensure a better administration of justice.
</P>
<P>
Secretary General of the OAS Cesar Gaviria said that the
ratification of both legal instruments "once again reveals Costa
Rica's avante guarde and democratic vocation when it comes to
protecting the fundamental rights of human beings." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
