<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Calls for 80 Million U.S. Dollars in Aid to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations has
called for 80 million U.S. dollars in aid to cover both
humanitarian activities and the operation of a 138-member U.N.
monitor contingent in Iraq, a U.N. spokesman said today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the appeal, U.N. Spokesman Sylvanan Foa said it was
presented to donors last Friday by Under-Secretary-General Yasushi
Akashi in a letter with a copy of the document "United Nations
Inter-Agency Humanitarian Programme in Iraq."
</P>
<P>
Foa explained that the appeal document was prepared in March
calling for 340 million U.S. dollars over the period April 1996 to
March 1997. It was decided to delay the launch of the appeal until
the outcome of the negotiations between U.N. and Iraq over
oil-for-food talks became clear.
</P>
<P>
According to the document, before the implementation of the
oil-for-food deal, the needs of vulnerable population should be
addressed.
</P>
<P>
"Some 80 million dollars are urgently needed to cover immediate
needs for food, water supply and sanitation, agricultural and
health services, as well as shelter and education," Foa said.
</P>
<P>
"In addition, funding for the operation of the U.N. Guard
Contingent in Iraq will be exhausted this months," she added.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Guard Contingent was established right after the
Gulf War through an agreement by the Iraqi government and
U.N secretariat. It is assinged to help protect U.N. relief
convoys and personnel in Iraq's three northern provinces where
it has no effective control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
