<HEADLINE> Clinton Reaffirms U.S. Support for Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton has
reaffirmed leaders of major Arab nations in the Middle East of the
continued U.S. support for a lasting and comprehensive peace in
the region, the White House said today.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry told reporters that Clinton
made the commitment in his last weekend letters to President Hosni
Mubarak of Egypt, King Hussein of Jordan, President Hafez Assad of
Syria and Palestinian Authority Leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Clinton assured the leaders "that the United States remains
committed to a comprehensive, just and lasting peace in the
region," McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also said that the Clinton administration was
"encouraged" by the conciliatory tone of Israel's new prime
minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
After his election as Israel's new leader last week, Netanyahu
held separately telephone talks with U.S. President Clinton and
Secretary of State Warren Christopher, and assured them that he
would continue to pursue the U.S.-backed peace process in the
Middle East. 
</P>
</TEXT>
