<HEADLINE> Perry Recommends New U.S. Navy Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William
Perry has recommended President Bill Clinton several replacements
for Adm. Jeremy "Mike" Boorda as the next chief of the U.S. Navy,
Pentagon officials said today.
</P>
<P>
The officials, who asked not to be identified, told reporters
that Clinton might announce "as early as Tuesday" a replacement
for Boorda, the former chief of the U.S. Navy who committed
suicide on May 16.
</P>
<P>
Although the Pentagon has kept secret Perry's recommendations,
the officials predicted that the Pentagon chief was leaning
toward Adm. Jay Johnson, 51.
</P>
<P>
Johnson, a former commander of the 2nd Fleet and a 1968
graduate of the U.S. Navy Academy, became Boorda's second in
command as vice chief of Naval operations and the youngest
four-star admiral in the U.S. Navy.
</P>
<P>
Johnson has temporarily taken charge of the U.S. Navy since
Boorda's death.
</P>
<P>
The other recommendations include Adm. Leighton Smith, who
presently is the top commander of the U.S.-led 60,000-strong NATO
peace implementation force in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Boorda shot himself in the chest in the backyard of his home at
the Washington Navy Yard after reporters accused him of having no
right to wear "V" for valor medals on his campaign ribbons under
the Navy rules. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
