<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Developing Countries Face Worsening Tobacco-Related </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) --The World Bank gave a warning
today that number of people worldwide who die from tobacco-related
diseases will rise from 3 million at present to 10 million by
2025, of which 7 million in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"Within three decades in developing nations, tobacco use may
kill more people than AIDS, tuberculosis and complications from
childbirth combined," said Dr. Richard Feachem, Senior Adviser in
the World Bank's Human Development Department.
</P>
<P>
While commenting on a World-Bank-sponsored conference on
"Avoiding the Epidemic of Non-Communicable Diseases," Feachem
added that "tobacco consumption is falling in most Western
countries but is rising in the developing world and tobacco
companies already target developing countries."
</P>
<P>
Of the world's 1.1 billion smokers in the early 1990s, about
800 million, or almost 75 percent of the total, live in the
developing nations. In developing countries, about 50 percent of
deaths in 1990 were caused by NCDs, but by 2020, that proportion
is expected to shoot up by 77 percent.
</P>
<P>
Many developing countries are eager to address the issue and
are already beginning to spend more money on the NCDs disease
control. The World Bank is also trying to deal with this emerging
problem. This conference is the first intensive forum to share
information on the ways the international community can pursue
anti-smoking policies and seek for low-cost, effective ways to
reduce the burden of NCDs, such as cardiovascular disease and
cancer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960604.0317 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Situation Improves In Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(By Pei Shanqin)
</P>
<P>
KIGALI, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations headquarters
have reclassified the security status for Rwanda from the 3rd
category to 1st category which permits UN agencies staff members
to bring their family members to Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
This was announced here today by the UNDP Representative and
Resident Co-ordinator of the United Nations System in Rwanda,
Sukehiro Hasegawa.
</P>
<P>
Hasegawa told reporters that the implications of the decision
to reclassify the security status in the most part of the country
are positive.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that the following areas are excluded from
the reclassified status, such as Ruhengeri, Cyangugu, Kibuye and
Gisenyi.
</P>
<P>
According to UN classification, restrictions of UN staff
movement are now no longer applicable in areas classified in
category one in the country, which has satisfactory security.
</P>
<P>
Hasegawa also said the improved security status for Rwanda
would provide an incentives to private investors to increase
their investment in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
